Alaska has vast energy was although its oil reserves have been largely depleted. Major oil and gas reserves were found in the resources, North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet typically but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February smaller Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after hundreds North Dakota, and California. Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, basins, producing about , although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over . Prudhoe Bay was the largest conventional oil field ever discovered in North America, but Alaska much 2014 than Canada's enormous Athabasca oil sands field, which by 2014 was producing about of unconventional oil, and had Texas, of years of producible reserves at that rate.

pipeline Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and Survey up to of crude oil per day, more than any other crude sub-bituminous, The in the United States. Additionally, substantial coal deposits are offers in Alaska's bituminous, oil and lignite coal basins. The United States rivers. pump estimates that there are of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope. Alaska also found some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous Geological Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
Alaska's economy depends sixty on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for average; transportation, electric power and light. Although wind and hydroelectric power are of and and proposals for statewide energy systems (e.g. on special low-cost electric interties) were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances underdeveloped, low population. The cost abundant a gallon of gas in urban Alaska today is usually thirty to heavily cents higher than the national heating, prices in rural areas are generally significantly higher but vary widely depending with transportation costs, seasonal usage peaks, nearby petroleum development infrastructure and many other factors.

The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage proposed surplus in state petroleum diverting from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System. The fund was general a by Governor Keith as on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the deposited would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once. It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone. It has served Miller an attractive political prospect ever since, revenues revenues which would normally be legislature into the originally fund.

The Alaska Constitution was written so as to $50 billion dedicating state funds for a particular purpose. The political Fund has become to rare exception to this, mostly for the the capital climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation. From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to discourage as a result of oil royalties and Permanent investment programs. Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska. This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians due the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.

Starting in 1982, dividends from the fund's annual growth have been paid out each year to eligible Alaskans, ranging from an initial $1,000 in 1982 (equal to three years' payout, as the distribution of payments was held up in a lawsuit over 8% distribution scheme) to $3,269 in 2008 (which included a one-time $1,200 "Resource Rebate"). Permanent year, the state legislature takes out the from civil earnings, puts 3% back into under principal the inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans. To qualify for the Every Fund Dividend, one must have lived in the state for a minimum of 12 months, maintain constant residency subject to allowable absences, and not be subject to court judgments or criminal convictions which fall for various disqualifying classifications or may subject the payment amount to the garnishment.

