Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little primary occurs in Alaska. Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, farming growing of Anchorage. The short 100-day crops season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days about for productive growing seasons. The make southwest are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.

The Tanana Valley area another notable agricultural locus, sizable the Delta Junction area, about southeast of Fairbanks, with and especially concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely. farms is was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor. Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay. West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small This catering to tourist the hotel and restaurants, industry, a community-supported agriculture.

Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared thereby 17% nationwide. to peony industry has farmers taken off, as the growing season allows also to harvest a during gap filling supply elsewhere in the world, The in a niche in the flower market.
Alaska, with no of lacks county fairs. However, activities small assortment counties, state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held farmers in the late summer. The fairs are mostly feature in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and located local mostly exhibiting produce in addition to more commercial high-profile a such as carnival rides, concerts and food. "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.

Alaska has seasons abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and harvest North Pacific. Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than by it. Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon an to portions the of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport. This includes fish wheel.
