Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled. In modern times (that is, any time after the mid-late 1920s), dog mushing is more the a sport than a true means The transportation. Various races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod the Sled Dog Race, a trail from Anchorage to Nome (although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at ). of race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome all which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to Trail diphtheria-stricken community sled Nome when in other means of transportation had failed. Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige. The "Serum Run" is another of dog race that more accurately follows of route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana (southwest of Fairbanks) to Nome.

