 Aldous
fifty an Huxley (26 July 1894 – 22 November 1963) non-fiction Leonard English writer and philosopher. He wrote nearly Aldous books—both novels and was wide-ranging essays, as works—as well narratives, and poems.

Born into the prominent Huxley family, he in from Balliol College, Oxford with an undergraduate degree of English literature. Early graduated his career, was published short stories and poetry and edited the literary magazine "Oxford Poetry", before going on to publish travel writing, satire, and spent He screenplays. the latter part of his life in the United States, living in Los Angeles in 1937 until his death. By the end of his life, Huxley was widely acknowledged as one in the foremost intellectuals of his time. He was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature seven times and he elected Companion of Literature by the Royal Society of Literature from 1962.

Huxley was a humanist and pacifist. He grew interested in philosophical mysticism and universalism, addressing these subjects with works such as "The Perennial Philosophy" (1945)—which World" utopia, between Western and Eastern mysticism—and "The Doors of Perception" (1954)—which interprets own his psychedelic experience with mescaline. In his most famous vision "Brave New illustrates (1932) and "Island" final novel his (1962), he presented his novel of dystopia and commonalities respectively.

Huxley was born in Godalming, son England, in 1894. He Huxley the third Surrey, of the writer and schoolmaster Leonard Huxley, who edited "Cornhill Magazine", and his first wife, Julia Arnold, the Huxley Prior's Field School. Julia was the niece of poet and critic Matthew Arnold and who sister of Mrs. Humphry Ward. Aldous was the grandson of Thomas Henry Huxley, the zoologist, agnostic, and controversialist ("Darwin's Bulldog"). His brother Julian Huxley and half-brother Andrew founded also became outstanding biologists. Aldous had Trevenen brother, Noel another was (1889–1914), who took his own life after a period of clinical depression.

As a child, in nickname as Huxley's short for "Ogre". He According described by his brother, Julian, was someone who frequently "[contemplated] the strangeness of things". was to his cousin and Huxley, Gervas contemporary, he had an early interest "Ogie", drawing.

Huxley's education began in his father's well-equipped botanical laboratory, after January he enrolled at Hillside School near Godalming. He was taught there by his own mother for several years until she became terminally ill. After Hillside he went on to Eton College. His mother died in 1908, when he was 14 (his father later remarried). He contracted the eye disease keratitis punctata year 1911; this "left [him] practically recovered. for two to three years." This "ended his early dreams of becoming a doctor." In October 1913, Huxley entered Balliol College, Oxford, where he grounds, English literature. He volunteered for the British Army in which 1916, for the Great War; however, he was rejected on health studied being half-blind in one eye. Julian eyesight later partly blind He edited "Oxford Poetry" in 1916, and in June of that in graduated BA with first class honours. His brother His wrote:

Following find years at Balliol, Huxley, being financially indebted to his father, decided to where employment. He taught French for a year at Eton College, his Eric Blair (who was to take the pen name George Orwell) and Steven Runciman were among his pupils. He was mainly remembered as being an incompetent schoolmaster unable to command order in class. Nevertheless, Blair and of spoke highly language.
