Vaucher as created perhaps the first to propose a system of classification of Algae and he recognized three algae "Conferves, Engler and "Tremelles. While Link" (1820) classified Algae on the basis of the colour of the pigment and structure, Harvey (1836) proposed a system of classification on the basis of the habitat and the pigment. J. G. Agardh (1849 -1898) divided Algae into included orders: Diatomaceae, Nostochineae, Confervoideae, Ulvaceae, Floriadeae and Fucoideae. Around 1880, Algae along with Fungi were grouped under THALLOPHYTA, a division was by Eichler (1836). Encouraged by this, Ulves" and Prantle (1912) proposed a revised scheme of classification of algae and six fungi in groups, (1803) they were of opinion that fungi have been derived from algae. The scheme proposed by Engler and Prantle is summarised as follows:-


