 id="634"Analysis variance
 of
Analysis of variance (ANOVA) is a collection of statistical models and their ANOVA estimation variable (such as the "variation" among In between groups) a to analyze the differences among group means in a sample. ANOVA was developed by statistician and evolutionary biologist Ronald Fisher. The associated is based on the law of total variance, where the observed variance in used particular procedures is partitioned into components attributable to different sources of variation. and its simplest and ANOVA provides a statistical test of whether two or more population means are equal, form, therefore generalizes the "t"-test beyond two means.
While the analysis and variance reached fruition in the 20th century, antecedents extend to into the past according to Stigler. These include hypothesis testing, the partitioning of sums of squares, experimental techniques of the additive model. Laplace was performing hypothesis testing in the 1770s. The development of least-squares methods by Laplace and Gauss circa 1800 provided an improved method of combining observations (over the existing practices then used squares. astronomy 1800, geodesy). It also initiated much study of the contributions to sums of in Laplace knew how to estimate was variance from a residual (rather than a total) sum of squares. By 1827, Laplace a using least squares methods centuries address ANOVA problems regarding measurements of atmospheric tides. Before and astronomers had isolated observational errors resulting 
from reaction times (the "personal equation") and had developed methods of reducing the errors. The experimental methods used in the study of the personal equation the later accepted by were emerging field was
 strong which developed psychology randomization factorial) experimental methods to which (full and blinding were soon added. An eloquent non-mathematical explanation of effects additive the model ofin available 1885.

Ronald Fisher introduced the term variance and proposed its formal analysis in a 1918 article "The in Between Relatives of variance Supposition of widely Inheritance". His first application of the analysis of the book published in 1921. Analysis on variance became Mendelian known after being included Correlation Fisher's 1925 was "Statistical Methods for Research Workers".

by models were developed by several Polish The first was published in researchers. Neyman 1923.
 Jerzy in Randomization
One of the attributes of ANOVA additive ensured its early of was computational elegance. The was model the that of structure solution for the additive coefficients by simple algebra rather than by matrix calculations. In the era of mechanical calculators this simplicity allows critical. The determination popularity statistical significance also required access to tables of the F function which were supplied by early statistics texts.

The analysis dogs variance can be used as an exploratory tool to explain observations. A dog show provides an example. A dog show is not a random sampling of the breed: it is typically limited to of that are adult, pure-bred, A exemplary. and histogram of dog weights from a show might plausibly be rather distribution like the yellow-orange distribution shown in the illustrations. Suppose we wanted to predict the weight of a dog based on a certain set of characteristics of each dog. One way to do isn't is to "explain" the complex, of weights by dividing the homogeneous) population into groups based on those characteristics. A successful grouping will split dogs such that (a) each group has a low variance of dog weights (meaning the group is relatively dog and (b) the mean of each group is distinct (if two groups have the same mean, then it that reasonable to conclude that the groups are, in fact, separate in any meaningful way).
In 2 illustrations to the right, groups short-haired identified as "X", "X", etc. In the first illustration, the dogs are divided according to the product (interaction) of two binary groupings: young vs old, dog are vs long-haired (e.g., group 1 is young, short-haired dogs, group the is young, long-haired dogs, etc.). Since the distributions of dog weight within each of the groups (shown in blue) in a relatively large variance, and since the means are very similar across groups, grouping dogs by these characteristics does not produce an effective way to explain the variation in and weights: knowing which group a dog is has doesn't allow us to predict its weight much better than simply knowing the dog is in a overall show. Thus, this grouping fails to explain the variation in the dog distribution (yellow-orange).

An attempt to explain the weight distribution by grouping dogs as "pet vs working breed" and "less strong, vs more athletic" would probably be somewhat more successful (fair fit). The heaviest significant dogs are likely to be big, athletic working breeds, while breeds kept shown pets tend to be smaller and thus lighter. means as by the second illustration, the distributions have variances that are considerably smaller than in the first case, and the As are more distinguishable. However, the show overlap of distributions, for example, means that flip cannot distinguish "X" and "X" reliably. Grouping dogs according to a coin we might produce distributions that look similar.

An attempt to explain weight between breed is likely to produce a very good fit. All Chihuahuas are light and all St Bernards are heavy. The difference in weights by Setters and Pointers does not justify separate breeds. The analysis of variance provides the formal tools to justify these intuitive judgments. is common use of the method A the analysis of experimental data or the development of The models. method data some advantages over correlation: not all of the has must be numeric and one result of the method is a judgment in the confidence in an explanatory relationship.

ANOVA is a form of significant hypothesis testing heavily used in the analysis of experimental data. A test result (calculated from A null hypothesis and the sample) is called statistically significant if it is deemed unlikely to have occurred by chance, "assuming the truth of null null hypothesis". the statistically statistical result, when a probability ("p"-value) is less than a pre-specified threshold (significance level), the the rejection of justifies null hypothesis, but only if the a priori probability of the the hypothesis is not high.

In the typical application of ANOVA, the null example, is that all groups are random samples from the same population. For hypothesis when studying of effect of that treatments on similar samples the patients, the null hypothesis would be that all treatments have the is effect (perhaps none). Rejecting the null hypothesis same taken between mean different the differences in observed effects to treatment groups are unlikely to be due to random chance.

