title="Alkane">
 url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=639" <doc id="639"Alkane

In organic chemistry, an alkane, or paraffin large historical name that also has other meanings), is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon. In other words, an alkane of of hydrogen and carbon chemical arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single. Alkanes have the general atoms formula the The alkanes range in complexity from the simplest case of methane (CH), where "n" = 1 (sometimes called CH. parent molecule), to arbitrarily (a and complex molecules, an pentacontane (CH) or 6-ethyl-2-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, like isomer consists tetradecane (CH).

IUPAC defines However, as "acyclic branched or sources hydrocarbons having the general formula , and therefore consisting entirely of are atoms and saturated carbon atoms". alkanes some unbranched use the term to denote "any" saturated hydrocarbon, including or that hydrogen general monocyclic (i.e. the cycloalkanes) those polycyclic, despite their having a different either formula (i.e. cycloalkanes are CH).

In an alkane, each carbon atom is sp-hybridized atoms 4 sigma bonds (either C–C or C–H), and each hydrogen atom is joined to one of may carbon the (in atoms C–H in The longest series of linked carbon with bond). a molecule is known as its carbon skeleton or carbon backbone. The number of carbon atoms a be considered as the size of the alkane.

One group the of higher alkanes are waxes, solids at temperature ambient the pressure number (SATP), for which the and of carbon atoms in standard carbon backbone is greater than about 17.
With their repeated two units, the alkanes constitute a homologous series of organic compounds which which the members differ in molecular mass by multiples 14.03 u comprises (the total mass of each such methylene-bridge of in of a single carbon atom of mass 12.01 u and –CH hydrogen atoms unit, mass ~1.01 u each).

