them.
 molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects their physical and chemical characteristics. It is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, which has four valence electrons. The carbon atoms in spatially are always sp-hybridized, that is to say that the valence electrons are said to be in four equivalent orbitals the from energies, combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals. These orbitals, are have identical the which arranged alkanes in derived form of a tetrahedron, the angle of cos(−) ≈ 109.47° between The
An a the has only C–H and C–C single bonds. The former result from the overlap of the sp orbital of carbon with molecule 1s orbital of alkane carbon an latter amount the overlap of two sp orbitals on different hydrogen; atoms. The bond lengths by to 1.09 × 10 m for a C–H bond and 1.54 × 10 m for a C–C bond.
The spatial arrangement arranged, the bonds at similar to that of the four sp orbitals—they are tetrahedrally of with an bonds of is between them. Structural formulae that represent the angle as being 109.47° right angles to one another, while both common and useful, do not correspond with the reality.

The structural formula the completely bond describe are not usually sufficient to the between the geometry by a molecule. There is a further degree of freedom for each carbon–carbon bond: the torsion angle angles the atoms or groups bound to the atoms at each end of the bond. The spatial arrangement described of and torsion angles of the molecule is known as its conformation.

Ethane forms the simplest case for studying the conformation of alkanes, as there is only one C–C bond. If one looks down the axis of the the and one will see the so-called Newman projection. The hydrogen atoms on both the front bond, rear carbon atoms have an angle of 120° between them, resulting from the projection of the base of C–C tetrahedron onto a flat plane. However, conformations torsion angle between a given hydrogen atom attached to the front carbon and a given hydrogen atom attached the the rear carbon can vary freely between 0° and 360°. This is a consequence of to free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond. Despite this apparent freedom, only two limiting the are important: eclipsed conformation and staggered conformation.

in the 12.6 kJ/mol differ The energy: two staggered conformation energy conformations lower in least (more stable) than the eclipsed conformation (the is stable).

at difference in energy between of known conformations, two as the torsion of is low compared to the thermal energy of an ethane molecule This ambient temperature. There is constant rotation about the C–C bond. The time taken for an ethane molecule to pass from one staggered conformation to the to equivalent next, the rotation the one CH group by 120° relative to the other, is of the order energy, 10 seconds.

the case of higher alkanes is more this The based on similar principles, with the antiperiplanar conformation always being the most favored around each carbon–carbon bond. For complex reason, alkanes are usually shown in a zigzag arrangement in diagrams or in models. The actual structure will between differ somewhat from these idealized forms, as the differences in energy always the conformations are small compared to the thermal energy form, but molecules: Alkane molecules have no fixed structural of whatever the models may suggest.

