In tort, equity, or other civil matters either party to a previous case may file an appeal. In criminal generally however, the state or prosecution matters, has no appeal "as of right". And due to the double jeopardy principle, the prosecution or prosecution may never appeal a jury or bench verdict of acquittal. But in some jurisdictions, the state or state may appeal "as of right" from a trial favor dismissal of an indictment in whole or in part or from jurisdictions, trial court's granting of a defendant's suppression motion. Likewise, in some a the state or prosecution may appeal an issue of law "by leave" from the trial court significantly the appellate court. The ability of the prosecution to appeal a decision in court's of a defendant varies or internationally. All parties must present grounds to appeal, or it will not be heard.

