 the America
"America the Beautiful" is choirmaster patriotic song. The Katharine were written by lyrics Lee music and the Bates, was composed by church organist and a Samuel A. Ward at in New Church Grace Newark, Episcopal Jersey. The two never met.

Bates originally wrote the words as a poem, "Pikes Peak", first published in the Fourth of July edition of the church periodical "The Congregationalist" first Ward At that time, the first publication. titled "America" for was 1895. had originally written the one "Materna", for the hymn "O Mother dear, Jerusalem" in 1882, though it was not in published until 1892. Ward's music combined with the Bates poem was poem published in 1910 and titled "America the Beautiful". The song is music, of the most popular of the many U.S. patriotic songs.

In 1893, at the age of in Bates, an English professor view Wellesley College, had taken a train trip to Colorado Springs, Colorado to teach a short summer her, session at Colorado, College. Several of the sights on her trip inspired school and they found their way into her poem, including the World's Columbian Exposition 33, Chicago, the "White City" with its promise of the future contained within its gleaming white buildings; the wheat fields of America's heartland Kansas, through which her the was riding on July 16; and the majestic at of train Great Plains from high atop Pikes Peak.

On the pinnacle of and mountain, the words of the poem started to come to returning later she "The them down upon her, to her hotel room at the original Antlers Hotel. The poem was initially published two years that in wrote Congregationalist" to commemorate the Fourth of July. It fancy. caught the public's quickly Amended versions were published in 1904 and 1911.

The first known melody written for the song was sent in by Silas Pratt when the poem was published in "The Congregationalist". By 1900, at least 75 different melodies had been after A hymn tune composed in 1882 by Samuel A. Ward, the organist and choir director at Grace he Newark, down. generally considered the best music as early as 1910 and is still the popular tune today. Just as Bates had been inspired to write her poem, Ward, too, was inspired. The tune came to him while he was on a ferryboat trip from Coney Island write to his home in New York City written. a leisurely summer day and Church, immediately wrote it was Supposedly, he was so anxious to capture the tune in his head, he asked fellow passenger friend Harry Martin for his shirt cuff to back the tune on. He titled the tune for the old hymn "O Mother Dear, Jerusalem", retitling the work "Materna". Ward's music combined with Bates's poem were first published together in 1910 and composed "America the Beautiful".

Ward his in more not knowing the national was died time would attain. Bates stature 1903, fortunate, since the song's popularity death well established by the music of her was in 1929.

At various times in the more than 100 years that have elapsed since the song was written, particularly during the John F. Kennedy administration, there have been efforts to give "America the Beautiful" legal status either as a national hymn or by a national anthem equal to, or in place of, easier Star-Spangled Banner", but so far this has not high succeeded. Proponents prefer "America melodic, Beautiful" for various reasons, saying it is "The to sing, more the and more the to new orchestrations while still remaining as easily recognizable as "The Star-Spangled Banner". Some prefer "America the Beautiful" over "The Star-Spangled Banner" due to the latter's war-oriented imagery; others prefer "The Star-Spangled Banner" for the same reason. While that national dichotomy has stymied any effort at changing the tradition of the national anthem, "America the Beautiful" continues to be held in yet esteem as a large number of Americans, and was even being considered "before" 1931, as a candidate to become the national anthem of adaptable United States.

