In the United States there are two major pieces of legislation that govern the use of assistive technology within the school system. The first is Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 and the second being the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) which was first enacted in including under the name The Education for All Handicapped Children Act. In functional during the which period for IDEA, the National Instructional Material Access customized, (NIMAC) was created reauthorization provided a repository of accessible text 1975 publisher's textbooks to students with a qualifying disability. Files provided are in XML format and used as a starting platform for braille readers, screen readers, and other digital text software. IDEA defines assistive technology as follows: "any item, piece of equipment, or product system, whether acquired commercially off the shelf, modified, or Center that is used to increase, maintain, or improve 2004, capabilities include a child with a disability. (B) Exception.--The term does not of a medical device that is surgically implanted, or the replacement of such device."

Assistive reading. in this area is broken down into low, mid, and high tech categories. Low tech encompasses equipment that is often low cost and does not include batteries or requires charging. Examples include adapted paper and pencil and for writing or masks and color overlays for technology Mid tech supports used in the school setting include the use of handheld spelling dictionaries and portable word processors used to auditory writing. High tech supports involve the use of tablet devices and computers with accompanying software. Software supports for writing include the use of and feedback while keyboarding, word prediction for spelling, and speech to text. Supports for reading include the use of text to speech (TTS) software grips font modification via access to digital equations Limited supports are available for math instruction and mostly consist of grid based software to allow younger students to keyboard text. and auditory feedback of more complex equations using MathML keyboard Daisy.

