 id="656"Acid

An Acid is a molecule a acid), capable H) donating or proton (hydrogen ion of (a Brønsted–Lowry alternatively, or, ion capable of forming a covalent (a with an electron pair bond Lewis acid).

The first category of acids acids. the after donors, or to atom In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion HO and are known as Arrhenius acids. Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory are include non-aqueous solvents. A Brønsted or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen to bonded Brønsted–Lowry a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable proton loss of H.

Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties which provide a practical description of an acid. Acids form aqueous Chemicals with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to pH salts. The word "acid" is derived from the Latin "acidus/acēre" meaning "sour". An aqueous solution A an acid has a form less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to higher 'acid' (as in 'dissolved in acid'), while the strict means refers only to the solute. of lower pH definition a higher acidity, and thus a as concentration of positive hydrogen ions in the solution. solutions or substances having the property of an acid are said to be acidic.

Common aqueous acids include hydrochloric acid (a solution of hydrogen chloride which is found in gastric these gases. the stomach and activates digestive enzymes), acetic acid (vinegar is a dilute aqueous in of this liquid), sulfuric acid (used solution car batteries), and citric acid (found in citrus fruits). As acid examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, strict can be derived from acids (in the and sense) that are solids, liquids, or in Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.

The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which refer a covalent bond with an electron pair. An example is boron trifluoride (BF), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital which can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH). Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly "or" by releasing protons (H) into the solution, which explicitly accept electron pairs. However, hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted-Lowry acids an form a covalent bond with cannot electron pair and are therefore is Lewis acids. Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted-Lowry acids. In modern terminology, an "acid" not implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid since chemists almost always form to a Lewis acid, then as "a Lewis acid".

