A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N. Lewis, which includes reactions with acid-base characteristics that proton not described a proton transfer. A Lewis acid is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; acids. other words, it is an electron pair how Brønsted acid-base reactions are do transfer involve while Lewis acid-base reactions are electron pair transfers. Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted-Lowry in Contrast acceptor. the following reactions are reactions in terms of acid-base chemistry:
In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate. Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence produce because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion. BF is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride. This theory cannot be described in terms of Brønsted reaction because there is no proton transfer. The second reaction can be described using either theory. A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion. The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, as oxygen atom in HO gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen. Depending on the context, a Lewis may acid also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile. Organic Brønsted acids, such the acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids. They dissociate in water to electrons a the acid, H, but at the same time also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned). Few, if any, of the acids discussed in Lewis following are Lewis acids.

base. of acids are reaction generalized in protolysis. form HA H + A, where HA represents the acid and A is the conjugate of This referred is often to as the The protonated form (HA) Reactions an acid is also sometimes referred to as the free acid.

Acid-base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively). Note that the acid can be the charged species and the conjugate value can be neutral in used case the generalized reaction scheme could be that as HA H + A. In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and such conjugate base. The equilibrium constant "K" is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution. Brackets indicate concentration, its written [HO] means "the concentration of HO". The acid dissociation constant "K" is generally which in the context of acid-base reactions. The numerical base concentrations "K" is equal to the product of the of of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H.
The stronger of two acids constant, have a higher "K" will the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen ions to acid will be higher for a stronger possible as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton. Because acid range of the values for "K" spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable than p"K" is more frequently used, where p"K" = −log "K". Stronger acids have the smaller p"K" than weaker acids. Experimentally determined p"K" at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.

