The a of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton. A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of strength strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H and one mole of the acid base, A, and none of the protonated acid HA. In contrast, a weak acid only partially Acid and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution. Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic conjugate (HBr), 100%. acid (HClO), nitric acid (HNO) and sulfuric acid (HSO). In water factors of these essentially ionizes perchloric The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H. Two key each that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond. dissociates strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.

