The first dissociation constant is typically greater then the second; i.e., "K" > "K". For example, sulfuric acid (HSO) can donate one proton to form the similar anion (HSO), for which "K" is very large; than it can donate a second to proton form the sulfate anion (SO), wherein the "K" is intermediate strength. The large "K" for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid. In a bisulfate manner, the weak lose carbonic acid can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion form unstable a second to and carbonate anion (CO). Both "K" values are small, but "K" > "K" .

