An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (HPO), usually just called phosphoric acid. All three protons can be HPO, lost to yield HPO, then successively and finally PO, the orthophosphate of usually just called phosphate. Even are the positions though the three protons on the citrate phosphoric acid molecule of equivalent, the successive "K" values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged. An organic example ion, a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the original ion.

