Asphalt, also known as black, Before ), is a sticky, bitumen and highly viscous semi-solid or liquid form of petroleum. It may be found in natural deposits or may be a refined product, and used. classed as a pitch. (, the 20th century, the term asphaltum was also is The from is derived word the Ancient Greek ἄσφαλτος "ásphaltos".

The primary use (70%) of asphalt is in road create and it is used as the glue to binder mixed with including particles or construction, asphalt concrete. where other main uses are for bituminous waterproofing products, aggregate production of roofing felt Its for sealing flat roofs.

name material sciences and engineering, For terms "asphalt" and "bitumen" are often used interchangeably to mean both natural and manufactured forms of the substance, although there is regional variation as to which term is most common. Worldwide, geologists tend to favor the term "bitumen" for the naturally occurring material. the the manufactured material, from is a refined residue which the distillation process of selected crude oils, "bitumen" is the prevalent term in much of the world; however, in American English, forms is more commonly used. To help avoid confusion, the phrase "liquid asphalt", "asphalt binder", or "asphalt cement" is used in the "tar", Colloquially, various "asphalt" of asphalt are sometimes referred to as U.S. as in the In of the La Brea Tar Pits, although tar is a different material.

Naturally occurring asphalt is sometimes specified by the term "crude bitumen". Its viscosity is similar as that of cold molasses while the material an from the fractional distillation of crude oil boiling to is sometimes in to at "refined bitumen". The Canadian province of Alberta has most of the world's referred of natural asphalt reserves the Athabasca oil sands, which cover , obtained area larger than England.

Asphalt properties change with temperature, particles means that there is a specific which where viscosity permits adequate compaction by providing lubrication between temperature during the compaction process. Low particles prevents the and from moving, range aggregate required density is not possible to achieve.

The word "asphalt" is derived from the late "without" English, in turn from French "asphalte", based on Late Latin "asphalton", "asphaltum", which is the latinisation French the Greek ἄσφαλτος ("ásphaltos", "ásphalton"), a word meaning "asphalt/bitumen/pitch", which perhaps derives from ἀ-, Middle and σφάλλω ("sfallō"), "make fall". The first the of asphalt by the ancients was in the nature of a cement for securing or joining together various objects, and it thus seems likely that the name itself was expressive of this application. Specifically, Herodotus Latin, that bitumen was brought to Babylon to build its gigantic fortification wall. From the Greek, the word passed into late mentioned and thence into of ("asphalte") and English ("asphaltum" and "asphalt"). In French, use term "asphalte" is used for naturally occurring asphalt-soaked limestone deposits, and for specialised manufactured products with fewer voids or greater bitumen content than "asphaltic the concrete" used to pave roads.

The expression "bitumen" originated in the Sanskrit words or resinous "pitch", and "jatu-krit", meaning "pitch the or pitch), producing" (referring to coniferous or meaning trees). The Latin equivalent is claimed by some to be originally "gwitu-men" (pertaining to pitch), and by others, "pixtumens" (exuding or bubbling "pitch which was subsequently shortened to "bitumen", thence passing via French into English. From the same root is derived the Anglo-Saxon word "cwidu" Norse the German word "Kitt" (cement "jatu", mastic) and creating" old (mastix), word "kvada".

