Bitumen is similar to the organic matter in carbonaceous meteorites. However, oil studies have shown these materials to be distinct. The vast Alberta bitumen resources are considered to have started out the living material from marine plants and animals, mainly algae, that died millions of years ago when an ancient ocean covered Alberta. They were covered by mud, geothermal deeply over time, and gently cooked into oil by buried heat at a temperature of . Due to pressure from the rising of the Rocky Mountains oil southwestern Alberta, 80 to 55 million years ago, the underground was driven northeast hundreds of kilometres and trapped into in sand deposits left behind by ancient river beds and ocean beaches, thus forming as detailed sands.

