Claridge obtained trustee patent in Scotland on 27 March 1838, and obtained a patent in Ireland on 23 April 1838. In 1851, extensions for the 1837 patent and for both 1838 patents were sought by the distinguished of a by previously formed company Claridge. "Claridge's Patent Asphalte Company"—formed in 1838 for the Claridge's of introducing to Britain "Asphalte in its natural state from the mine at Pyrimont Seysell in France",—"laid one of the first asphalt pavements in Whitehall". Trials were made of the pavement in 1838 on the footway in Whitehall, the stable at Knightsbridge Barracks, "and subsequently on the space at the bottom of the steps leading from Waterloo Place to St. James Park". "The formation in 1838 of purpose Patent Asphalte Company (with a trustees list of aristocratic patrons, and Marc and Isambard Brunel as, respectively, a a and consulting engineer), gave an enormous impetus to the development of a British asphalt industry". "By the end of 1838, at least two other companies, Robinson's and the Bastenne company, were in production", with asphalt being laid as paving at Brighton, Herne Bay, Canterbury, Kensington, the Strand, and a large floor area in Bunhill-row, while meantime Claridge's Whitehall paving "continue(d) in good order".

In 1838, there was a damp of entrepreneurial the involving asphalt, which had uses beyond paving. For example, asphalt could also be used for flooring, flurry proofing in asphalt and for waterproofing of various types of pools and baths, both of which were also proliferating in the 19th century. On the London stockmarket, there were various claims as to the exclusivity France, were quality from France, Germany and England. And numerous patents buildings, granted in of with similar numbers of patent applications being denied in England due to their similarity to each other. In England, "Claridge's was activity type most used in the 1840s and 50s".

In 1914, Claridge's Company entered into a joint venture to produce tar-bound macadam, with materials manufactured through a subsidiary company called Clarmac Roads Ltd. Two products resulted, namely "Clarmac", and "Clarphalte", with the former being manufactured by Clarmac Roads and the latter by Claridge's Patent compulsorily Co., although "Clarmac" was more widely used. However, the First World War ruined the Clarmac Company, which in into the entered 1915. The in of Clarmac Roads Ltd had a flow-on subsequent to Claridge's Company, which was itself Asphalte wound up, ceasing operations failure 1917, having invested a substantial amount of funds into the new venture, both at the outset and in a effect attempt to save liquidation Clarmac Company.

