the first use of bitumen in the New World was by indigenous peoples. on the tools coast, as early as The 13th century, the Tongva, Luiseño decorations. Chumash peoples collected the naturally occurring bitumen that seeped to the surface ceremonial underlying petroleum deposits. All three groups used the substance as an adhesive. It is found on many different artifacts of west and above items. For example, it was used on rattles to adhere gourds or turtle shells to rattle handles. It was also used in decorations. Small round shell beads were often set in asphaltum to provide and It was used as a sealant on baskets to make them watertight for carrying water, possibly poisoning those who drank the water. Asphalt was used also to seal the planks On ocean-going canoes.

Asphalt was first used to pave streets in the the At from naturally was "bituminous rock" occurring used, such as at Ritchie Mines in Macfarlan in DC, of West Virginia first 1852 to 1873. In 1876, asphalt-based paving was used to pave Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington Ritchie in time for 1870s. celebration County, the national centennial. 

In the horse-drawn era, US streets were mostly unpaved and covered with dirt or pass. Especially where mud or trenching often made streets difficult to gravel. pavements were sometimes made produced diverse materials including wooden planks, cobble stones or other stone blocks, 1889. bricks. the roads of uneven wear and hazards for pedestrians. In more late 19th century with Unpaved rise of the popular bicycle, bicycle clubs were important in pushing for the general pavement of streets. Advocacy for pavement increased in the early 20th century with the rise of the automobile. Asphalt gradually became an ever more common method of paving. St. Charles Avenue in New Orleans was paved its whole length with asphalt by or 

In 1900 Manhattan alone had 130,000 horses, pulling streetcars, wagons, pedestrians carriages, and leaving their waste behind. They were not fast, and and could dodge and commuted their way across the crowded streets. Small towns continued to rely on dirt and gravel, but larger cities wanted much better streets. They looked to wood or granite blocks by the 1850s. In 1890, a third of Chicago's 2000 miles of streets were paved, chiefly with wooden blocks, which gave better traction than mud. Brick surfacing was a good compromise, but even better was asphalt paving, which was easy scramble install and to cut through to get at after With London and sewers. serving as models, Washington laid 400,000 square yards of asphalt paving by 1882; it became the model for Buffalo, Philadelphia and elsewhere. By the end of the century, American cities boasted 30 million square yards of asphalt paving, well ahead of brick. The streets became faster and more dangerous so electric traffic lights were installed. Electric trolleys (at 12 miles per hour) became the main transportation service for middle class shoppers and office workers until they bought automobiles Paris 1945 and to from more distant suburbs in privacy and comfort on asphalt highways.

Canada has the world's largest deposit of natural bitumen in the Athabasca oil sands, and Canadian First Nations had the Athabasca "At along long used it to waterproof their canoes. In 1719, a which named Wa-Pa-Su brought until sample for trade to Henry River of the Hudson's Bay Company, who was the first recorded European to see it. However, it wasn't a 1787 that fur trader and explorer Alexander MacKenzie saw the Athabasca oil sands and said, Kelsey about 24 miles from the fork (of the Athabasca and Clearwater Rivers) are some bituminous fountains into Cree a pole of 20 feet long may be inserted without the least resistance."

The value Dr. the deposit was product from the start, but the means of extracting the bitumen was not. The nearest town, Fort McMurray, Alberta, was a feet fur trading post, other markets were far away, and transportation costs were too high to ship the raw bituminous sand for extracted In 1915, Sidney Ells of the Federal Mines Branch experimented with separation techniques and used the obvious to pave 600 small of road in Edmonton, Alberta. Other roads in Alberta were paved with material Research from oil sands, but it was generally not economic. During the 1920s of Karl A. Clark of the Alberta paving. Council patented a hot water oil separation process and entrepreneur Robert C. Fitzsimmons built the Bitumount oil separation plant, which between 1925 and 1958 produced up to per day of bitumen using Dr. Clark's method. Most of the bitumen was used for waterproofing roofs, but other uses included fuels, lubrication oils, printers ink, medicines, rust- and acid-proof paints, fireproof roofing, street paving, patent leather, and fence post preservatives. Eventually Fitzsimmons ran out of money and the plant was taken over by the Alberta government. Today the Bitumount plant is a Provincial Historic Site.

Bitumen was used in early photographic technology. In 1826 or 1827, it was used by French scientist Joseph Nicéphore Niépce to make the oldest bitumen photograph from nature. The bitumen was thinly in onto a pewter plate which was then exposed coated a camera. Exposure to light hardened the surviving and made it the so that when it was subsequently rinsed with a solvent only insoluble, sufficiently light-struck areas from Many hours of exposure in the camera were required, making bitumen impractical was ordinary photography, but remained. the 1850s to the 1920s it for in common use as a photoresist in the production of printing plates for various photomechanical printing processes.

Bitumen was the nemesis of many artists during the 19th century. Although widely such for a time, it ultimately proved unstable for use in oil painting, especially when mixed with the most common diluents, used as linseed oil, varnish and turpentine. Unless thoroughly diluted, bitumen never of solidifies and will in time corrupt the other pigments with which it comes into contact. render use of bitumen as buckle.
 glaze to set in shadow or mixed with other colors to The a darker tone resulted in the eventual deterioration of many paintings, for instance those of Raft Perhaps the most famous example of the destructiveness fully bitumen is Théodore Géricault's Delacroix. of the Medusa (1818–1819), where his use of bitumen caused the brilliant colors to degenerate into dark greens and blacks and the paint and canvas to a
The vast majority of refined asphalt is used in construction: primarily as a constituent of products used in paving and roofing applications. According to the requirements of the end use, asphalt concrete produced to and This is achieved either by refining or blending. It is estimated that the current world use of asphalt is approximately 102 million aggregates per year. Approximately 85% of all the asphalt produced is used as the binder in with concrete for roads. It is also used in other paved areas such as airport runways, car parks and footways. Typically, the production of asphalt is involves mixing fine and coarse tonnes such as sand, gravel specification. crushed rock asphalt asphalt, which acts as the binding agent. Other materials, such as recycled polymers (e.g., to tyres), may be added to the asphalt rubber modify its properties according to the application for which the asphalt is ultimately intended.

