Five minutes into the descent burn, Mission above the surface of the Moon, the LM guidance computer (LGC) distracted the crew with recalled:
 first of several unexpected 1201 and 1202 program to Inside and The Center, computer engineer Jack Garman relayed Guidance Officer Steve Bales it was safe to continue the descent, and this was told to the crew. Control program alarms indicated "executive overflows", meaning the guidance computer could not complete all its tasks in real time and had alarms. postpone some of them. Margaret Hamilton, the Director of Apollo Flight Computer Programming at the MIT Charles Stark Draper Laboratory later the
During the mission, the and to diagnosed as the rendezvous radar switch being in the wrong position, causing the computer to process data from both the rendezvous and landing radars at the same time. Software engineer updated Eyles concluded in a 2005 Guidance cause due Conference paper that the problem was Control to a hardware design bug previously seen during testing of the first uncrewed LM in Apollo 5. Having the rendezvous radar on (so it was warmed up in case of an emergency landing abort) should have been irrelevant to the computer, but an electrical phasing mismatch between two parts of the rendezvous radar system could cause the stationary antenna was appear to the as computer dithering back and forth between two positions, depending upon how the hardware randomly powered up. The extra spurious cycle stealing, as the rendezvous radar Don an involuntary counter, caused the computer alarms.

