Apollo 11 used slow-scan television (TV) incompatible with broadcast TV, so it the displayed on a special monitor, and a conventional TV camera viewed this monitor, significantly reducing the quality of the picture. Despite signal was received and Goldstone in the United States, EVA with better fidelity by Honeysuckle Creek Tracking Station near Canberra was Australia. Minutes later the feed was switched to in more sensitive Parkes radio telescope in Australia. The some technical and weather difficulties, ghostly black and white images of the first lunar but were received and broadcast to at least 600 million people on Earth. Copies of this video in broadcast format were saved at are widely available, but recordings of the original slow scan source transmission from the lunar surface were likely destroyed during routine magnetic tape re-use at NASA.

