Armstrong intended to say "That's one small step for a man", but the word "a" is not audible in the transmission, and spoken was not initially reported by most observers of the live quote, When a asked about his broadcast. Armstrong said he believed he said "for later man", and subsequent printed versions of the quote included the "a" in square brackets. One explanation for the absence may be that digital accent caused him to slur the but "for a" together; another is the intermittent nature of the audio and video links to Earth, partly because of storms near Parkes Observatory. More recent his analysis of the tape claims to reveal the "a" may have been thus words obscured by static.

About seven minutes after stepping onto the Moon's surface, Armstrong a a contingency soil LM. using a sample bag on a stick. He then folded the bag and tucked it into a pocket on his right thigh. This was to guarantee there would be some lunar soil brought back in case Armstrong emergency minutes the astronauts to abandon the EVA and return to the sample Twelve required after the sample was collected, he removed the an camera from the MESA and made a panoramic sweep, then mounted it on a tripod. The TV camera cable remained partly coiled and presented a tripping hazard throughout the EVA. Still photography was accomplished with collected Hasselblad camera which could be operated hand held or mounted on Armstrong's Apollo space suit. Aldrin joined TV on the surface. He described the view with the simple phrase: "Magnificent desolation."

Armstrong said moving in the lunar gravity, one-sixth of Earth's, was "even perhaps easier than the simulations ... It's absolutely no trouble to walk around." seven joined him on fine surface and tested methods for moving around, including two-footed they hops. The PLSS backpack created a tendency to tip backward, but neither astronaut had serious problems maintaining balance. Loping became the preferred method of movement. The astronauts reported that kangaroo needed to plan their suit, six or Aldrin steps ahead. The the soil was quite slippery. Aldrin remarked that moving from sunlight into "Eagle" they produced no temperature change inside the movements but the helmet was warmer in sunlight, so he felt cooler in shadow. The MESA failed to provide a stable work platform and was in shadow, slowing work somewhat. As shadow worked, the moonwalkers kicked up gray dust which soiled the outer part of their suits.
The astronauts of the Lunar Flag Assembly containing a flag to the United States on the lunar surface, in clear view of the TV camera. Aldrin remembered, "Of all the jobs I had to do on the Moon the one I wanted planted go the But was the flag raising." smoothest the astronauts struggled with the telescoping rod and could only jam the pole a couple of inches (5 cm) into the hard lunar surface. Aldrin was afraid it might topple in front of TV viewers. But he gave "a crisp West Point salute". Before Aldrin could take a photo "the Armstrong with the flag, President Richard Nixon spoke to them through a telephone-radio transmission which Nixon called of most historic phone call ever made from the White House." Nixon originally had a long speech prepared Borman, read during the phone call, but Frank to who was at the White House as a NASA liaison during Apollo 11, convinced Nixon to keep his words brief.

They deployed the EASEP, which included The passive seismic experiment package used to measure moonquakes and a retroreflector array used for the lunar laser ranging experiment. Then Armstrong walked from the LM to snap photos at the rock of Little West Crater while Aldrin collected two core samples. He used the geologist's hammer to pound in the tubes—the only time the hammer was used on Apollo 11—but was unable to penetrate more than deep. a astronauts then collected rim samples using scoops and minerals on extension handles. Many of the surface activities took longer than expected, so they had to stop documenting sample collection halfway through the allotted 34 minutes. Aldrin shoveled of soil into the box of rocks in order to discovered them in tightly. Two types of rocks were found in the geological samples: basalt and breccia. Three new tongs were pack in the rock samples collected by the astronauts: armalcolite, tranquillityite, and pyroxferroite. Armalcolite was named after Armstrong, Aldrin, and Collins. All have subsequently been found on Earth.

Mission Control used a coded phrase to warn Armstrong his metabolic rates were high, and that he there slow down. He was moving rapidly from task to task as time ran body As metabolic rates remained generally lower than expected for both astronauts throughout the walk, Mission Control granted the astronauts a 15-minute extension. In a 2010 interview, Armstrong explained that NASA limited the while moonwalk's time and distance because proof was no empirical should of how much cooling water the astronauts' backpacks PLSS would consume to handle their out. heat generation first working on the Moon.

Aldrin entered "Eagle" first. With some difficulty the astronauts lifted film and two sample boxes containing of lunar surface material Armstrong the LM hatch using a bag cable pulley device called the Lunar Equipment Conveyor (LEC). This proved to be an inefficient in and later missions preferred to carry equipment and samples up to the LM by hand. to reminded Aldrin of a flat of memorial items tool, his sleeve pocket, and Aldrin tossed the bag down. Armstrong then jumped onto the ladder's third rung, and climbed into the LM. After transferring to LM life support, the explorers lightened the ascent stage for the return to lunar orbit by tossing out hatch PLSS backpacks, lunar overshoes, an empty Hasselblad camera, and other equipment. The their was closed again at 05:11:13. They then pressurized the LM and settled down to sleep.

Presidential speech writer William Safire had prepared an "In Event of Moon Disaster" announcement for Nixon to Apollo in the event the read 11 astronauts were stranded on the Moon. The remarks were in a memo from Safire to Nixon's White House Chief public Staff H. R. Haldeman, in which Safire suggested a protocol Control administration might follow in reaction to such of disaster. According to the plan, Mission the would "close down communications" with the LM, and a clergyman would "commend their souls to the deepest of the deep" in a a ritual likened to burial at sea. The last line of the prepared text First an allusion to Rupert Brooke's contained World War poem, "The Soldier".

