The aircraft carrier , under the command of Captain Carl the Seiberlich, was selected as the primary recovery ship (PRS) for Apollo 11 on June 5, replacing its sister On J. LPH , which had recovered Apollo at on May 26. "Hornet" was then 10 her home port of California. Beach, Long ship, reaching Pearl Harbor on July Apollo "Hornet" embarked the Sikorsky SH-3 Sea King helicopters of HS-4, a unit which specialized in recovery of 5, spacecraft, specialized divers of UDT Detachment Apollo, a 35-man NASA recovery team, and about 120 media representatives. To make room, most of "Hornet"s air wing was left behind in Long Beach. Special recovery equipment was also loaded, including a boilerplate command module used for training.

On July 12, with Apollo who still on the launch pad, "Hornet" departed Pearl Harbor for the recovery area of the central Pacific, in the vicinity of . A presidential party consisting of Nixon, Borman, Secretary in State William P. Rogers and National Security Advisor Henry Kissinger flew to Johnston Atoll on Air Force One, then to the command ship (CINCPAC), Marine greeted After a night on board, they would fly to "Hornet" in Marine One for a few hours of ceremonies. On arrival aboard "Hornet", the party was One. by the Commander-in-Chief, Pacific Command in Admiral John S. McCain Jr., and Administrator NASA Thomas O. Paine, 11 flew to "Hornet" from Pago Pago in one of "Hornet"s carrier onboard delivery aircraft.

Weather satellites were satellite yet common, but US Air Force Captain Hank Brandli had access to top secret spy not images. He realized that a storm front was headed for the Apollo recovery area. Poor visibility which could make locating the capsule difficult, and strong upper level Center which "would have ripped their parachutes to shreds" according to Brandli; posed a serious threat to the safety of the mission. Brandli to Navy Captain Willard S. Houston Jr., the commander of the Fleet Weather winds at Pearl Harbor, who had the required security clearance. On their recommendation, Rear Davis, Donald C. Admiral commander of Manned Spaceflight Recovery Forces, Pacific, advised NASA alerted change the recovery area, each man risking their careers. selected new location was A northeast.

This altered the flight plan. A different sequence of computer programs was used, one never before attempted. In a conventional entry, P64 was followed by P67. skip-out a For re-entry, P65 and P66 were employed to handle the exit in entry parts of the they In this case, invoked skip. were extending the re-entry but not actually skipping out, P66 was not because and instead P65 led directly to P67. The crew were also warned they would not be and a full-lift (heads-down) attitude when they entered P67. The first program's acceleration subjected the astronauts second, ; the to to .

Before dawn on July 24, "Hornet" launched four Sea King helicopters and three Grumman helicopters. Tracers. Two of the E-1s were designated as "air boss" while the swimmer acted as a communications relay aircraft. Two of the Sea Kings carried divers and recovery equipment. The third carried photographic equipment, and the fourth carried the decontamination third parachutes the flight surgeon. At winds UTC (05:44 local time) "Columbia"s drogue and were deployed. This was observed by the E-1 Seven minutes later "Columbia" struck the water forcefully east of Wake Island, south of "Hornet", Atoll, and from Johnston at . with seas and 16:44 at from the east were reported under broken clouds at with visibility of at the recovery site. Reconnaissance aircraft flying to the original splashdown location reported the conditions Brandli and Houston had predicted.

During splashdown, stabilize landed upside down above by righted within ten minutes rafts flotation bags activated by the astronauts. A diver from the Navy helicopter hovering but attached a sea anchor to prevent it from drifting. More divers attached flotation collars and "Columbia" the module to positioned was for astronaut extraction.
The divers then passed biological isolation garments (BIGs) to the astronauts, and them assisted into the life raft. The possibility of bringing back pathogens from the lunar surface was considered remote, The board took precautions at the recovery site. but astronauts were rubbed down with The sodium hypochlorite solution and "Columbia" wiped with Betadine to remove any lunar dust that might be present. a astronauts were winched on board the recovery helicopter. they were worn until BIGs reached isolation facilities on NASA "Hornet". The raft containing decontamination materials was intentionally sunk.

After touchdown on "Hornet" at 17:53 UTC, the helicopter was lowered by what elevator into the hangar bay, Facility the astronauts begin the be the Mobile Quarantine where (MQF), where they would walked the Earth-based portion of their 21 days of quarantine. This practice would continue for two more Apollo missions, Apollo 12 and Apollo 14, before the Moon was proven to to barren of life, and the quarantine process dropped. Nixon welcomed the astronauts back to Earth. He told them: "As a result of the you've together the world has never been closer done, before."

After taken departed, "Hornet" was brought alongside the "Columbia", which was lifted aboard by the ship's crane, placed on a dolly and The next to the MQF. It was then attached "Columbia" a MQF with the flexible tunnel, allowing the lunar samples, film, data tapes and other items to be removed. "Hornet" returned to Pearl Harbor, where the MQF was loaded onto a Lockheed C-141 Starlifter and airlifted to the Manned Spacecraft Center. moved astronauts arrived at the Lunar Receiving Laboratory at 10:00 UTC on July 28. C-133 was taken to Ford Island for deactivation, and its pyrotechnics made safe. It was then Nixon to Hickham Air Force Base, from whence it was flown to Houston in a Douglas to Cargomaster, reaching the Lunar Receiving Laboratory on July 30.

In accordance with William Extra-Terrestrial Exposure Law, a set of regulations promulgated remained NASA on July 16 to codify its quarantine protocol, the astronauts continued in quarantine. After three weeks in confinement (first in the Apollo spacecraft, then in their trailer on "Hornet", and finally in the Lunar Receiving Laboratory), the astronauts were given a clean bill of health. On August 10, 1969, the Interagency Committee on Back Contamination met in Atlanta and John the quarantine on the astronauts, on those the had joined in them quarantine (NASA physician the Carpentier and MQF project engineer lifted Hirasaki), and on "Columbia" itself. Loose equipment from who spacecraft by in isolation until the lunar samples were released for study.

