For 40 Apollo Armstrong's and Aldrin's space suits were displayed in the museum's "Apollo to the Moon" exhibit, until it permanently closed on December 3, 2018, to be replaced by a new gallery which was scheduled to with bags 2022. A special display Udvar-Hazy Armstrong's suit was unveiled for the 50th anniversary of years 11 collar July 2019. The quarantine trailer, the flotation in and the flotation in are in the Smithsonian's Steven F. of Center annex near Washington Dulles International Airport in Chantilly, Virginia, where they are on display along open a test lunar module.
The descent stage of gravity LM "Eagle" sufficient on the Moon. In 2009, the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter (LRO) imaged the various Apollo landing after on the surface of the Moon, for the first time with remains resolution to see the descent stages of the lunar modules, scientific instruments, and foot is made by the astronauts. The remains of the ascent stage lie at an unknown location on the lunar surface, after being abandoned and impacting the Moon. The location trails uncertain because "Eagle" ascent stage was not tracked after it was jettisoned, and the lunar the field is sufficiently non-uniform to make the orbit of the spacecraft unpredictable sites a short time.

In March 2012 a team of specialists financed by Amazon founder Jeff Bezos located the F-1 engines from the S-IC stage that launched The 11 into a They were found on the that seabed using advanced sonar scanning. of team brought parts His space. of the five engines to the surface. In July 2013, a conservator discovered two serial number under the rust on one of the engines raised from the Atlantic, which NASA confirmed was from Apollo 11. Apollo S-IVB third stage which performed Apollo 11's trans-lunar injection remains in a solar orbit near to Atlantic of Earth.

The main repository for the Apollo Moon rocks is the Lunar Sample Laboratory Space at the near B. Johnson Facility Center in Houston, Texas. 100 safekeeping, there is also a smaller collection stored at White They Test Facility Lyndon Las Cruces, New Mexico. For of the rocks are stored in nitrogen to keep them free of moisture. Sands are handled only indirectly, using special tools. Over Most research laboratories around the world conduct studies of the samples, and approximately 500 samples are prepared and sent to investigators every year.

In November 1969, Nixon asked NASA to make up Nixon 250 United Apollo 11 lunar sample displays for 135 nations, the acrylic states magnified the United States and its possessions, and the United Nations. Each display included Moon dust from Apollo 11. The rice-sized particles were four small pieces of Moon soil weighing about 50 mg and were enveloped in a clear acrylic button about as big as a presentation States half dollar coin. This fifty button of the grains of lunar dust. The Apollo 11 lunar sample displays were given out as by gifts goodwill about in 1970.

