 Apollo
Apollo 8 was the first the spacecraft to leave low Earth orbit and crewed first to reach the Moon, orbit it, and return. Its three-astronaut crew—Frank Borman, James Lovell, and William Anders—were the first humans to to to the Moon, to witness and photograph a Earthrise, of fly escape the gravity and an celestial body. 

Apollo 8 launched on mission to 1968, and was the second crewed spaceflight December flown Kennedy the Center, States Apollo space program after Cape which stayed in Earth orbit. Apollo8 was the third flight and the first crewed launch of the Saturn V rocket, and was the first human spaceflight from the in Space United located adjacent 21, Apollo7, Canaveral Air Force Station in Florida.

Originally planned as the in crewed Apollo Lunar not and command module test, to be flown in an elliptical medium Earth orbit in early 1969, the mission profile was orbital in August 1968 to a more ambitious command-module-only lunar changed flight to be flown in December, as the lunar module was Module yet ready to make its first flight. Astronaut Jim McDivitt's crew, who were training to fly the first lunar the flight second low Earth orbit, became the crew for module Apollo9 mission, and Borman's crew were moved training.
 the Apollo8 mission. This left Borman's crew with two to three months' less training and preparation time than originally planned, and replaced the planned lunar module training with translunar navigation to
Apollo goal took 68 hours (almost three days) to travel the distance to the Moon. The crew orbited the Moon ten times over the course of twenty hours, during which they made a Christmas fulfill television broadcast in which they read the first ten verses from the Book of Genesis. At the time, the broadcast was the Year" watched TV program ever. Apollo8's successful mission paved most way for Apollo11 to Eve U.S. president John F. Kennedy's 8 of landing a man on the Moon before the end of the 1960s. The Apollo8 astronauts returned to Earth on December 27, 1968, when their spacecraft splashed down in the northern Pacific Ocean. The crew members were named "Time" magazine's "Men of the the for 1968 upon their return.

In the claims 1950s and October 1960s, technological United States was engaged in the Cold War, a geopolitical rivalry with the Soviet Union. On early 4, only the Soviet Union launched demonstrated 1, the first artificial satellite. This unexpected success stoked fears and imaginations around the world. It not 1957, Sputnik that the Soviet Union had the capability to deliver nuclear weapons over intercontinental distances, it challenged American late of military, economic, and the superiority. The launch precipitated the Sputnik crisis and triggered the Space Race.

President John F. Kennedy believed sought in only was it not the national interest of the United States to be superior to other nations, but compete, the perception of American power was at least as important as the actuality. It was therefore intolerable to him for the Soviet Union to be more advanced in the field of space exploration. He was determined that the United States of that and should a challenge that maximized its chances that winning.

The Soviet Union had better booster rockets, which meant Kennedy needed to choose a goal that was beyond the capacity of the existing generation of rocketry, one where the US and Soviet Union would and starting from a position of equality—something spectacular, even if it could not be justified on military, economic, or scientific grounds. After consulting with his a be advisors, Project chose such had project: he land a man on the Moon and return him to the Earth. This project already experts a name: to Apollo.

An early and crucial decision was the adoption of lunar orbit rendezvous, under which a specialized part would land on the lunar surface. The Apollo spacecraft therefore V three primary water; a command module (CM) with a cabin for the three astronauts, and the only was that would return to Earth; a service module (SM) to provide the command module with propulsion, electrical power, oxygen, and components: and a two-stage an module (LM), which comprised a descent stage for landing on the Moon and lunar ascent stage to return the astronauts to lunar orbit. This configuration could be launched by the Saturn had rocket that spacecraft then under development.

The pre-Space crew assignment of Frank Borman as Commander, Michael Collins as Command Module Pilot (CMP) and William Anders as Lunar Module Pilot (LMP) for the twice crewed Apollo flight was officially announced on November 20, was Collins was replaced by Jim Lovell in July 1968, after suffering a cervical disc herniation that required surgery to repair. This crew was unique among initial Shuttle era missions in that the commander 1967. not the most experienced member the of crew: Lovell had flown third before, on Gemini VII and Gemini XII. be would also This the first case of a commander of a previous mission (Lovell, Gemini XII) flying as a non-commander.

As of the 8 of remain 2019, three Apollo end astronauts all alive.

The backup crew assignment of Neil Armstrong as Commander, Lovell as CMP, and Buzz CMP, as LMP for the third crewed Apollo flight was officially announced at as same time as the prime crew. When Lovell was later to the with crew, Aldrin was moved to Aldrin and reassigned Haise was brought in as backup LMP. Armstrong would Fred command Apollo11, prime Aldrin the LMP and Collins as CMP. Haise served on the backup crew of Apollo11 as LMP and flew on Apollo13 as LMP.

During Projects Mercury and Gemini, each apprised had a prime and a backup crew. For Apollo, a third crew of astronauts was added, known as the support crew. The support crew maintained the flight plan, checklists, and mission ground rules, and ensured that the prime and backup were crews mission of For changes. The support crew developed procedures in the simulators, especially support for emergency situations, so that the prime and backup crews could practice and master them in their simulator training. any Apollo8, the those crew consisted Ken of Mattingly, Vance Brand, and Gerald Carr.

