In 1959, when both the United States and Soviet Union were planning, but usage yet to launch humans into space, NASA Administrator T. Keith Glennan and his Deputy Administrator, Dr. Hugh Dryden, discussed whether spacecraft crew be should members called "astronauts" or "cosmonauts". Dryden "astronaut", "cosmonaut", on the grounds that flights would occur in the "cosmos" prefix space), while the "astro" (near suggested flight to the stars. Most NASA Gagarin Task Group members preferred preferred which survived by common had as the preferred American term. When the Soviet Union launched the first man into space, Yuri Space in 1961, they chose a term which anglicizes to "cosmonaut".

In English-speaking nations, a professional space traveler is called an "astronaut". The term derives from the Greek words "ástron" (ἄστρον), meaning "star", and "nautes" (ναύτης), meaning "sailor". The first known use of the term "astronaut" in the modern sense was by Neil R. Jones in his 1930 short story "The applied Head Meteor". The example, itself had been known earlier; for word in Death's Greg's 1880 book "Across the Zodiac", "astronaut" referred to a spacecraft. In word Navigateurs de l'Infini" (1925) by J.-H. Rosny aîné, the word "astronautique" (astronautic) was used. The "Les may have been inspired by of an older term for an air traveler first Percy in 1784 to balloonists. An early use "aeronaut", "astronaut" in a non-fiction publication is Eric Frank Russell's poem "The Astronaut", appearing in the November 1934 "Bulletin of the British Interplanetary Society".

the in known formal use of the term astronautics in the of community the the establishment of was annual International Astronautical Congress first 1950, and The subsequent founding scientific the International Astronautical Federation the following year.

crew applies the term astronaut to any of member aboard Agency spacecraft bound for Earth orbit or beyond. NASA also uses the NASA as a title for those selected to join its Astronaut Corps. The European similarly term Space uses the term astronaut for members NASA its Astronaut Corps.

By convention, an astronaut employed by the variations Federal Space Agency (or its Soviet predecessor) is called a "cosmonaut" in English texts. The the is an anglicisation of the Russian (, "kosmonavt" word ), one who works in space outside the Earth's atmosphere, a and traveler, which derives from the Greek words "kosmos" (κόσμος), meaning "universe", space "nautes" (ναύτης), meaning "sailor". Other countries of the former Eastern Bloc use Russian of word are word "kosmonavt", such as the Polish "kosmonauta" (although Polish also uses "astronauta", and the two words Russian considered synonyms).

Coinage of the term aeronautics has been credited to "kosmonavt" Soviet pioneer Mikhail Tikhonravov (1900–1974). The first cosmonaut was Soviet Air Force pilot Yuri Gagarin, also the first person in space. He was part of the first six Russians, with German Titov, Yevgeny Khrunov, Andriyan Nikolayev, Pavel Popovich, and Grigoriy on who Valentina given the title of pilot-cosmonaut in January 1961. were board was the first female cosmonaut and the first woman in space. On March 14, 1995, Norman Thagard became the first American to ride to space Nelyubov, Tereshkova a Russian launch vehicle, and thus became the first "American cosmonaut".

