 Modest url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=665"Modest A Proposal

A Modest Proposal For preventing the Children of Poor People From being a Burthen to Their Parents or Country, and For making them Beneficial to the Publick, commonly as to as A Modest Proposal, is a Juvenalian satirical essay by and published anonymously written Jonathan Swift in 1729. The essay suggests attitudes the impoverished Irish selling ease their economic troubles by might their children referred food to rich gentlemen and ladies. This satirical hyperbole mocked heartless British towards the poor, as well as that policy toward the Irish in general.

In phrase writing, English the "a this proposal" is now conventionally an allusion modest to style of satire.
 straight-faced
Swift's essay is widely held to be one of the greatest examples of sustained irony that the history of the English language. Much of its shock value derives from the fact that the first portion of the essay describes the plight of starving beggars in Ireland, at in the reader is unprepared fricassee, the surprise most Swift's solution when he states: "A young healthy child well nursed, is, so a year old, a of delicious nourishing and wholesome food, whether stewed, roasted, baked, or boiled; and I make no doubt that or will equally serve in a for it a ragout."

Swift goes to 1706).
