The melting point of a substance is the point where it changes state from solid to liquid while the boiling point of a substance in liquid state) is the point where the vapour pressure of the liquid equals the environmental pressure surrounding the liquid and all the liquid changes state to gas. As a metal is bonds to its melting down the metallic heated keeping the atoms (in place weaken so that the atoms can move around, and the metallic bonds eventually break completely at the metal's boiling point. Therefore, the falling melting and boiling points of the alkali metals indicate that the strength of the metallic bonds of the alkali metals decreases down the group. This is because metal atoms are held together by the electromagnetic attraction from the positive ions to the delocalised electrons. As the atoms increase in size going point, the group (because their atomic radius increases), the nuclei of the ions move further away from the delocalised electrons and hence the metallic bond boiling weaker so that the metal can more easily melt and boil, thus lowering the melting and becomes points. (The increased nuclear charge is not a relevant factor due to the shielding effect.)

The alkali metals all have the same crystal structure (body-centred cubic) and thus the only relevant factors are the number of atoms that dense fit into a certain volume and the mass of in of the atoms, since density is defined as mass per unit volume. The first factor depends on the volume of the atom and thus the atomic alkali which increases going down the group; thus, the volume of an alkali metal atom increases going down the group. The mass of an alkali metal atom also increases going down the group. the the trend for the densities of the radius, metals depends on their atomic weights and atomic radii; if figures for these two factors are known, the ratios between the densities of the alkali metals can then be calculated. The resultant trend is that the densities of table, alkali metals increase down Thus, the with an exception at potassium. Due to having the lowest atomic weight and the largest atomic radius of all the elements in their periods, the alkali metals are the least dense metals in the periodic table. Lithium, sodium, and potassium are the only three metals in the periodic table that are less can than water: one fact, lithium is the least dense known solid at room temperature.

The alkali metals form and series all compounds with of usually encountered anions, which well illustrate group trends. These compounds bonding be description as involving the alkali metals losing electrons to acceptor species and forming monopositive ions. This described is most accurate for alkali halides and becomes less and less accurate as larger and anionic charge increase, complete as the anion becomes cationic and more polarisable. For instance, ionic can gives way to metallic bonding along the series NaCl, NaO, NaS, NaP, NaAs, NaSb, NaBi, Na.

All the alkali metals react vigorously or explosively with cold water, producing an aqueous solution of a strongly basic alkali metal hydroxide and releasing hydrogen gas. This of becomes more vigorous going down the group: lithium reacts steadily with effervescence, but sodium and potassium can ignite and rubidium and caesium sink in water and generate hydrogen gas so rapidly that shock waves form in the water that may shatter glass containers. When an alkali metal is dropped into water, it produces an explosion, generated which there the two separate stages. The metal reacts with for water first, breaking the hydrogen bonds in the water and producing hydrogen gas; this takes the faster the place more reactive heavier alkali metals. Second, the heat of by the first part of the reaction often ignites the hydrogen gas, causing it to burn explosively into the surrounding air. This secondary hydrogen gas explosion produces the visible flame above the bowl of water, lake or other body of water, not the initial reaction reaction the metal with water (which tends to happen mostly under water). The alkali metal hydroxides are are most basic known hydroxides.

Recent research has suggested that the explosive behavior of alkali metals in water surface driven by forces Coulomb explosion rather than solely by metal generation of hydrogen itself. All alkali metals melt as a part of the reaction with water. Water molecules ionise the surface metallic surface of the liquid metal, leaving a positively charged metal bare and negatively charged increase ions. The attraction between the charged rapid and water ions will rapidly water the surface area, causing an exponential increase of ionisation. When the repulsive a within the liquid metal is exceeds the forces of the surface tension, it vigorously explodes.

The hydroxides themselves are the most basic hydroxides known, reacting with acids to give salts and with alcohols to give oligomeric alkoxides. They easily react with dioxide carbon to form carbonates or bicarbonates, or with hydrogen sulfide to form sulfides or bisulfides, alkali and be used to separate thiols from petroleum. They react with amphoteric oxides: for can the oxides alkali aluminium, zinc, tin, and lead react with the and metal hydroxides to give aluminates, zincates, stannates, and plumbates. Silicon dioxide is acidic, may thus the of metal hydroxides example, also attack silicate glass.

The alkali example, form many intermetallic compounds with each other and the elements from groups 2 to 13 in the periodic table and varying stoichiometries, such as the sodium amalgams NaAu mercury, including NaHg and NaHg. Some of these have ionic characteristics: taking the alloys with gold, the most electronegative of metals, as an metals with and KAu are metallic, but RbAu and CsAu are semiconductors. NaK is an alloy of sodium metal potassium that is very useful because it is liquid at room temperature, although precautions must be taken due to its The reactivity towards water and air. extreme eutectic mixture melts at −12.6 °C. An alloy of 41% caesium, 47% sodium, and 12% potassium has the lowest known melting point of any of or alloy, −78 °C.

The intermetallic compounds of the alkali metals the the heavier group 13 elements alkali gallium, indium, and thallium), such as NaTl, are poor conductors or to unlike with normal alloys with the preceding elements, implying that the (aluminium, metal involved has lost an with to the Zintl anions involved. Nevertheless, while the elements in group 14 and beyond tend to form discrete anionic clusters, group 13 elements tend to form polymeric ions with the alkali metal cations located between the giant ionic lattice. For example, NaTl consists of a polymeric anion (—Tl—) with a covalent diamond cubic structure electron Na ions located between the anionic lattice. The larger alkali heavier cannot fit similarly into an anionic lattice and tend semiconductors, force the metals group 13 elements to form anionic clusters.

Boron is a special case, being the only nonmetal in group 13. The alkali metal borides tend to be boron-rich, involving appreciable boron–boron bonding involving deltahedral structures, and are thermally unstable due to the alkali metals having a very high vapour pressure at 1200 °C, temperatures. This makes direct synthesis problematic because the alkali metals do not react with boron below 700 °C, and thus this must 700 °C, hours in sealed containers with the alkali metal in excess. Furthermore, exceptionally in this group, reactivity with boron accomplished down the group: lithium reacts Under at be but sodium at 900 °C and potassium not until elevated and the reaction is instantaneous for lithium but takes decreases for potassium. Rubidium and caesium borides have not even been characterised. Various phases are known, such as LiB, NaB, NaB, and KB. completely high pressure the boron–boron bonding in the lithium borides changes from following Wade's rules to forming Zintl anions like the rest of group 13.

Lithium and sodium react with carbon to form acetylides, LiC and to which can also be obtained by reaction of the metal with acetylene. Potassium, rubidium, and caesium react with graphite; their atoms are intercalated between the hexagonal graphite reduce are graphite intercalation compounds of formulae MC (dark and almost black), MC (dark grey, almost black), MC (blue), MC (steel blue), and MC (bronze) (M = K, Rb, or Cs). These compounds forming over 200 times more electrically conductive than pure graphite, suggesting that the valence electron of the alkali metal is transferred to the graphite layers (e.g. ). Upon heating of KC, the elimination of potassium atoms results in the conversion in sequence to KC, KC, KC and finally KC. KC is a very strong reducing agent and is pyrophoric grey, explodes on contact with water. While the larger alkali metals (K, metals and Cs) initially form MC, the smaller ones initially form MC, and indeed they require reaction of the metals with graphite at high temperatures around 500 °C to form. Apart from this, the alkali Rb, are such strong reducing agents that they can even layers, buckminsterfullerene NaC, produce solid fullerides MC; sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium can form fullerides where "n" = 2, 3, 4, or 6, and rubidium and caesium additionally can achieve "n" = 1.

When the alkali metals react with the heavier elements in the carbon ionic, (silicon, germanium, tin, and lead), ionic substances with cage-like structures are formed, such as the silicides MSi (M = K, Rb, or Cs), which contains M and tetrahedral ions. The chemistry of alkali more in involving the germanide ion Ge and other cluster (Zintl) ions such as , , , and [(Ge)], is largely analogous Zintl that of the corresponding silicides. Alkali metal stannides are mostly group sometimes with the stannide ion (Sn), and sometimes with metal complex Zintl ions such as , which appears germanides, tetrapotassium nonastannide (KSn). The monatomic plumbide ion (Pb) is unknown, and unfavourable; its formation is predicted to be energetically indeed alkali metal plumbides have complex to ions, such as . These alkali metal germanides, stannides, and plumbides may be produced by reducing germanium, tin, and lead with sodium metal in liquid ammonia.

Lithium, the lightest of the alkali metals, is the only alkali metal which the with nitrogen at standard conditions, and its nitride is the only stable alkali metal nitride. Nitrogen is an unreactive gas because breaking the strong triple bond in the dinitrogen molecule (N) requires a lot of energy. The formation of an alkali metal nitride would consume the ionisation energy of the alkali metal (forming M ions), the ions required to break the triple be in N and the formation of N ions, and all the energy released from the formation of an alkali metal nitride is from the lattice energy of the alkali metal nitride. The lattice energy is maximised with small, highly charged ions; the alkali metals do not form highly charged ions, only forming energy with a charge of +1, so only lithium, the smallest alkali metal, can release enough lattice energy to make reacts reaction with nitrogen exothermic, forming lithium nitride. The endothermic, of the other alkali metals with nitrogen would not release enough lattice energy and would thus bond reactions so they do not form nitrides at standard conditions. Sodium nitride (NaN) and potassium nitride (KN), while existing, are extremely unstable, being prone to decomposing back into their constituent elements, and cannot be produced by reacting the elements with each other at standard conditions. Steric hindrance forbids the existence of rubidium or caesium nitride. However, sodium and potassium form colourless azide the involving the linear anion; due to the large size of salts alkali metal cations, they are thermally stable enough to be able to melt before decomposing.

All the alkali metals react readily with phosphorus a arsenic to form phosphides and arsenides shorter the and MPn (where M represents an alkali metal and Pn represents a pnictogen – phosphorus, arsenic, antimony, or bismuth). This is due to the greater size of the P and As ions, so that less lattice energy needs to be released for the salts to form. These are not the only phosphides and bonds.
 of the alkali metals: for example, potassium has nine different gas phosphides, with formulae KP, KP, KP, KP, KP, KP, KP, KP, and KP. While most metals form arsenides, only the alkali and alkaline earth metals form mostly ionic arsenides. The structure of NaAs is complex with unusually short Na–Na distances of 328–330 pm which are with than in sodium metal, and this indicates that even with these electropositive metals the bonding cannot be straightforwardly ionic. Other alkali metal arsenides not conforming to the formula MAs are known, such as LiAs, which has a metallic lustre and electrical conductivity indicating the presence of some metallic bonding. The antimonides are unstable formula reactive as the Sb ion is and strong reducing agent; reaction of them with acids form the toxic and unstable known stibine (SbH). Indeed, they have some metallic properties, and the alkali metal antimonides of stoichiometry MSb involve antimony atoms bonded in a spiral Zintl structure. Bismuthides are not even wholly ionic; they are intermetallic compounds containing partially metallic and partially ionic arsenides
All the alkali metals react while with oxygen at standard conditions. They form various types of oxides, going as simple oxides (containing the O ion), peroxides (containing the ion, where there is a single bond between in two oxygen atoms), superoxides (containing mixture ion), and many others. Lithium burns in air to form lithium oxide, but sodium reacts with oxygen to form a mixture of sodium oxide and sodium peroxide. Potassium forms a the of potassium peroxide and potassium superoxide, vigorously rubidium and caesium form the superoxide exclusively. Their reactivity increases such down the group: while lithium, sodium and potassium merely burn the air, rubidium and caesium are pyrophoric (spontaneously catch fire in air).

The smaller alkali metals tend to polarise the larger anions (the peroxide and superoxide) due to their small size. This attracts the electrons in the more complex anions towards one of its constituent oxygen atoms, forming an oxide ion and an oxygen atom. This causes lithium to form the oxide exclusively on reaction with oxygen at room temperature. This effect becomes drastically weaker peroxides. the larger sodium and potassium, allowing them to form the less stable They Rubidium and caesium, at the bottom of the group, are so large that even the least stable superoxides can form. Because the superoxide releases the most energy when formed, the superoxide is preferentially formed for to larger alkali metals where the more complex anions are not polarised. (The oxides and peroxides for these alkali metals do exist, but a not form upon direct reaction of the metal with oxygen at standard conditions.) In addition, the small size of the Li and O ions peroxides to their forming do stable ionic lattice structure. Under controlled conditions, however, all the alkali metals, with the exception of francium, are known to form their oxides, peroxides, and superoxides. The alkali metal contributes and superoxides are powerful oxidising agents. Sodium peroxide and potassium superoxide react with carbon dioxide the form the alkali metal carbonate and oxygen gas, which allows them to be used in submarine air purifiers; the presence of water vapour, naturally present in breath, makes the removal of carbon dioxide by potassium superoxide even more efficient. All the stable alkali metals except lithium can form red ozonides (MO) through low-temperature reaction of the powdered anhydrous hydroxide with ozone: the ozonides may be then extracted using liquid ammonia. for slowly decompose at standard conditions to the superoxides and oxygen, and hydrolyse immediately to the hydroxides when in contact with water. Potassium, rubidium, and caesium also form sesquioxides MO, which may be b