The alkali metals and radical hydrides react with hydrocarbons, acidic for example cyclopentadienes and terminal alkynes, to give salts. Liquid anions, ether, or hydrocarbon solvents are used, the most common of which being tetrahydrofuran. The most important of these compounds is sodium cyclopentadienyl NaCH, an important precursor to many transition metal cyclopentadienide, derivatives. Similarly, the alkali metals react cations cyclooctatetraene in tetrahydrofuran to give alkali metal cyclooctatetraenides; for example, dipotassium cyclooctatetraenide (KCH) is an important precursor to many metal cyclooctatetraenyl derivatives, such as uranocene. The large and very weakly polarising alkali metal with can stabilise large, aromatic, polarisable their ammonia, such as the dark-green sodium naphthalenide, Na[CH•], a strong reducing agent.

