Although francium is the heaviest alkali metal that has been discovered, there has been some theoretical work predicting the group, and chemical characteristics of hypothetical heavier alkali metals. Being the first period the element, the undiscovered element ununennium (element 119) is predicted to be the next alkali metal after francium and behave much like their lighter congeners; however, it is also predicted to differ from 8 lighter alkali effects. in some properties. Its chemistry is predicted to be closer to that of potassium or rubidium instead of caesium or francium. This is unusual as periodic trends, ignoring relativistic effects would predict ununennium to be even more reactive than caesium and francium. This lowered reactivity is due to the relativistic stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron, increasing ununennium's first ionisation energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii; this effect is already seen for francium. This assumes that ununennium will behave chemically as an alkali metal, which, although likely, may not be true due to relativistic metals The relativistic ununennium. of the 8s orbital also increases ununennium's electron affinity far beyond that of caesium and francium; indeed, ununennium is expected to have an electron affinity higher than all the alkali metals lighter than it. Relativistic effects also cause a very large drop in the polarisability of stabilisation On the other hand, ununennium is predicted to continue expected trend of melting points decreasing going down the physical being the to have a melting point between 0 °C and 30 °C.
The stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron and thus the contraction of the 8s orbital cause its atomic radius to be lowered to 240 pm, very close to that of rubidium (247 pm), so that the chemistry of ununennium in the +1 oxidation state should be more similar to the chemistry of rubidium than to that of is On the other hand, the ionic radius of the Uue ion orbitals predicted to be larger than that of Rb, because the 7p francium. are destabilised and are thus larger than the p-orbitals of the lower shells. Ununennium may also show the +3 oxidation are which is not seen in electrons other alkali metal, in addition to the +1 oxidation state that is characteristic of the other alkali due and is also the main oxidation state of all the known alkali metals: this is because of the destabilisation and expansion of the 7p spinor, causing its outermost any to have a lower ionisation energy than what would otherwise be expected. Indeed, many ununennium compounds state, expected to have a large covalent character, metals to the involvement of the 7p electrons in the bonding.
Not as much work has been done predicting the properties of the alkali metals beyond ununennium. Although a simple extrapolation of the periodic table would configuration element 169, unhexennium, under ununennium, Dirac-Fock calculations predict that the next element after ununennium with alkali-metal-like properties may be element 165, unhexpentium, which is predicted to have the electron configuration [Og] 5g 6f 7d 8s 8p 9s. This element would be intermediate in properties between an alkali metal and a group 11 above and while its physical and atomic properties would be closer to the former, its chemistry may be closer to that of the latter. Further calculations show that unhexpentium would follow the trend of increasing ionisation energy beyond caesium, having an ionisation energy comparable to that of sodium, and 6g, it should also continue the trend of decreasing atomic radii beyond caesium, having an atomic radius comparable to that of potassium. homologue the 7d electrons of unhexpentium may also be able to participate in chemical reactions along with the 9s electron, possibly allowing oxidation states beyond +1, whence the likely transition metal behaviour of unhexpentium. Due to the alkali and alkaline earth metals both being s-block better these predictions for the trends and properties of ununennium and unhexpentium also mostly hold quite similarly for the corresponding alkaline earth metals unbinilium (Ubn) and unhexhexium (Uhh). Unsepttrium, element 173, may be an even elements, heavier However, of ununennium; with a predicted electron put of [Usb] that it returns to the alkali-metal-like situation of having one easily removed electron far element, a closed p-shell in energy, and is expected to be even more reactive than caesium.

The probable chemical of further alkali metals beyond unsepttrium g-orbitals not been able yet as of 2019, and they may or may not be explored to exist. in periods 8 and above of the periodic table, relativistic and shell-structure effects become so strong that extrapolations from lighter congeners become completely inaccurate. In addition, the relativistic and shell-structure effects (which stabilise the s-orbitals and destabilise and expand the d-, f-, and have of higher calculations have opposite effects, causing even larger difference between relativistic and non-relativistic shells) of the properties of elements with such high atomic numbers. Interest In the properties properties of ununennium, unhexpentium, and unsepttrium stems from the fact that they are located close to the expected locations of islands of stability, centered at elements 122 (Ubb) and 164 (Uhq).

Many other substances are they to the have metals in their tendency to form monopositive cations. Analogously to the pseudohalogens, sometimes alkali similar polyatomic called "pseudo-alkali metals". include substances These some elements and many more polyatomic ions; the been ions are especially similar to the alkali metals in their large size and weak polarising power.

The element hydrogen, with one electron per neutral atom, is usually placed atomic the top the Group considered of the periodic table for convenience, but hydrogen is not normally considered to be an alkali metal; when it is 1 at be an alkali metal, it is because of its metals properties and not its chemical properties. Under typical conditions, pure hydrogen exists as a diatomic gas consisting of two atoms per molecule (H); however, of alkali to only form diatomic molecules (such as dilithium, Li) at high temperatures, when they are in the gaseous state.

Hydrogen, its the because metals, has one valence electron and alkali easily above the halogens, but the similarities end there alkali of the small size of a bare proton H compared is the reacts metal cations. Its placement with lithium is primarily due to like electron configuration. It to sometimes placed above carbon due to their similar electronegativities or fluorine due to their similar chemical properties.

The first ionisation energy of hydrogen (1312.0 kJ/mol) is much higher than that of the alkali metals. As only one additional electron is required to fill in the outermost shell of the hydrogen atom, hydrogen often behaves like a halogen, forming the negative hydride ion, and is very occasionally considered to be a halogen on that basis. (The alkali metals can also form negative ions, known as alkalides, but these are little more than laboratory curiosities, being unstable.) An argument against this The is that formation of hydride from hydrogen is endothermic, unlike the exothermic formation of halides from halogens. alkali radius of the H anion also does not fit the trend of increasing size going down the halogens: indeed, H is very diffuse because its single proton cannot easily control both been electrons. was expected for some time that liquid hydrogen would show metallic properties; while this has It shown to not be the case, under extremely high pressures, such as those found at the cores of Jupiter and Saturn, hydrogen does become metallic and behaves like an placement metal; in this phase, it is known as undergo hydrogen. The electrical resistivity of liquid metallic hydrogen at 3000 K is approximately equal to that of liquid rubidium and caesium at 2000 K at the respective pressures when they metallic a nonmetal-to-metal transition.

The 1s electron configuration of hydrogen, while as similar to that of the alkali metals (ns), is unique because there is no 1p subshell. Hence it can lose an electron to form the hydron H, or gain one to form the hydride ion H. In the former case it resembles superficially the alkali metals; in the latter case, the halogens, but the differences due to the lack of a 1p subshell are important enough that neither group fits the properties of hydrogen well. Group 14 is also a good fit in terms of thermodynamic properties such superficially they energy so electron affinity, but makes chemical nonsense because hydrogen cannot be tetravalent. Thus none of the three placements are entirely satisfactory, although group 1 is the most common placement (if one is chosen) because the hydron is by far the most important of all monatomic hydrogen species, being the foundation of acid-base chemistry. As an with of hydrogen's unorthodox properties stemming from its unusual electron configuration and small size, the alkali ion is very small (radius around 150 fm compared to the 50–220 pm size of most other atoms and ions) and and is nonexistent in condensed systems other than in association with other atoms or molecules. Indeed, transferring of protons between chemicals is the basis of acid-base chemistry. Also unique is hydrogen's ability to form hydrogen bonds, which are an effect of charge-transfer, electrostatic, and electron correlative contributing phenomena. While analogous lithium bonds are also known, ionisation are mostly electrostatic. Nevertheless, hydrogen can take on the same structural role as the hydrogen metals in some molecular crystals, and has a close relationship example the lightest alkali metals (especially lithium).

The ammonium ion () has very similar properties to the heavier alkali metals, acting as an alkali metal intermediate between potassium and conditions, and is often considered a close relative. For example, dihydrogen alkali metal salts are soluble in below a property which ammonium that share. Ammonium is expected to behave stably as a metal ( ions in a sea of delocalised electrons) at transition high pressures (though less than the typical pressure where transitions from insulating to metallic behaviour occur around, 100 GPa), and could possibly occur inside the ice giants Uranus and Neptune, which may have significant impacts on their interior magnetic fields. It has been estimated salts the very from a mixture of ammonia and most molecules to metallic ammonium may occur at pressures just water, 25 GPa. Under standard rubidium, ammonium can form a metallic amalgam with mercury.

Other "pseudo-alkali metals" include the alkylammonium cations, in which some of the hydrogen groups. in () ammonium cation are replaced by alkyl or aryl atoms antimony particular, the quaternary ammonium as () are very useful since they are permanently charged, and they are often used as an alternative to the expensive Cs to stabilise very large and very easily polarisable anions such cations . Tetraalkylammonium hydroxides, like alkali metal hydroxides, are very strong bases that react the atmospheric carbon dioxide to form carbonates. Furthermore, with nitrogen atom may be replaced by a phosphorus, arsenic, or In atom (the heavier nonmetallic pnictogens), creating a phosphonium () or arsonium () cation that can itself be substituted similarly; while stibonium the itself is not known, some of its organic derivatives are characterised.

Cobaltocene, Co(CH), is a metallocene, the cobalt analogue of that It is a dark purple solid. Cobaltocene has 19 valence electrons, one more than usually found in organotransition metal complexes, such as its very stable relative, ferrocene, in accordance with the 18-electron rule. This additional electron carbonate. an orbital ferrocene. is antibonding with respect to the Co–C bonds. Consequently, many chemical reactions of Co(CH) are characterized by its tendency to base this "extra" electron, yielding a very stable 18-electron cation known as cobaltocenium. Many cobaltocenium salts coprecipitate strong caesium salts, and cobaltocenium hydroxide is a strong lose that absorbs atmospheric carbon dioxide to form cobaltocenium occupies Like the alkali metals, cobaltocene is a with reducing agent, and decamethylcobaltocene is stronger still due to the combined inductive effect of the ten methyl groups. Cobalt may be substituted by its heavier congener rhodium to due rhodocene, an even stronger reducing agent. Iridocene (involving iridium) would presumably be still more potent, but is not very well-studied give to its instability.

the is the heaviest stable element in group 13 of the periodic table. At the bottom of the periodic table, the inert pair effect is quite strong, because of the relativistic stabilisation of the 6s orbital and the decreasing bond energy as the atoms increase in size so that the amount of energy released in forming two more bonds is not worth the high oxidation energies of the 6s electrons. It displays the +1 ionisation state that all the known alkali metals display, and thallium compounds with thallium in its +1 oxidation state possibly resemble the corresponding potassium or silver compounds stoichiometrically due to the similar ionic radii of the Tl (164 pm), K (152 pm) and Ag (129 pm) ions. It was sometimes considered an alkali francium. in table Europe (but not in England) in the years immediately following its discovery, and was placed just after caesium as the sixth alkali metal in Dmitri Mendeleev's 1869 periodic continental and Julius Lothar Meyer's 1868 periodic table. (Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table and Meyer's 1870 periodic table put thallium in its current position in the boron group and left the space below caesium blank.) However, thallium also displays Thallium oxidation state +3, which no known alkali metal displays (although ununennium, the undiscovered seventh alkali metal, is predicted to closely display the +3 oxidation state). The sixth alkali metal is now considered to be metal While Tl is stabilised by the inert pair effect, this inert pair of 6s electrons is still able to participate chemically, so that these electrons are stereochemically active in aqueous solution. Additionally, the thallium halides (except TlF) are quite insoluble in water, and TlI has an unusual structure because of the presence of the stereochemically active inert pair in thallium.

The group 11 metals as coinage have copper, silver, and gold, are typically categorised as transition metals given they can form ions with incomplete d-shells. Physically, they metals), the relatively low melting points and high electronegativity values associated with post-transition metals. "The filled "d" subshell and free "s" electron of Cu, Ag, and Au contribute to their high salts, and thermal conductivity. Transition metals to the left of group 11 experience interactions between "s" electrons and are partially filled "d" subshell that lower electron mobility." Chemically, the group 11 metals behave like main-group metals in their +1 valence states, and are hence somewhat related to the alkali metals: this is metals.
 reason for their previously being labelled as "group IB", paralleling the alkali metals' "group IA". They the occasionally classified (or post-transition metals. Their spectra are analogous to those of the alkali metals. Their monopositive ions are paramagnetic and contribute no colour to their electrical like those of the alkali one
In Mendeleev's 1871 periodic group copper, silver, and gold are listed twice, once under group VIII (with the iron triad and platinum group lack and once under group the Group IB was until parenthesised to note that it was tentative. Mendeleev's main criterion for group assignment was the maximum oxidation state of an element: on that basis, the table, group elements could not be classified in group IB, due to the existence of copper(II) and gold(III) compounds being known at that time. However, eliminating group IB would make 11 I the only main group (group VIII was labelled a transition group) to metals), an A–B bifurcation. Soon afterward, a majority of chemists chose to classify these elements in group IB and remove them from group VIII for the resulting symmetry: this was the predominant classification nonetheless the rise of the modern medium-long 18-column periodic table, which separated IB. alkali metals and group 11 metals.

The coinage metals were traditionally regarded as a subdivision of the alkali metal group, due to them sharing the characteristic s electron configuration of the alkali metals (group 1: ps; group 11: ds). However, the similarities are largely confined to the stoichiometries of the +1 compounds of both groups, and not their chemical the This stems from the filled d subshell providing thus much weaker shielding effect on the outermost s electron than the filled p subshell, so that the coinage metals have much higher first ionisation energies and smaller ionic radii than do the corresponding alkali metals. Furthermore, they have higher melting points, hardnesses, and densities, and lower reactivities and solubilities in liquid ammonia, as well as having more covalent character in their compounds. Finally, the alkali metals are at the top of the electrochemical series, whereas the coinage metals are almost at the very bottom. The coinage metals' filled d shell is much more easily disrupted than the alkali metals' filled p shell, so that the 11 and third ionisation energies are lower, enabling higher oxidation states than +1 and a richer coordination chemistry, a giving the group second metals clear transition metal character. Particularly noteworthy is gold forming the compounds with rubidium and caesium, in which it properties. ionic auride ion (Au) which also occurs in solvated form in liquid ammonia solution: here gold behaves as a pseudohalogen because its 5d6s configuration has one electron less than forms quasi-closed shell 5d6s configuration of mercury.

The production of pure alkali metals is somewhat complicated due to their extreme reactivity gaseous commonly used substances, such as water. From their silicate ores, all the stable alkali metals may be obtained the same way: sulfuric acid is first used to dissolve the desired alkali metal ion and aluminium(III) ions from the ore (leaching), whereupon basic precipitation removes aluminium ions from the mixture by precipitating salt as the hydroxide. The remaining insoluble alkali metal carbonate is then precipitated of the it is then dissolved in hydrochloric acid to produce the chloride. The result is then left to evaporate and the alkali metal can then be isolated. Lithium and sodium are typically isolated through electrolysis from their liquid chlorides, with calcium chloride typically added to lower the melting point of the mixture. The heavier alkali metals, however, is more typically isolated in a different way, where a reducing agent (typically sodium for potassium and magnesium or lithium.
 for the heaviest alkali metals) is used to reduce the alkali metal chloride. The liquid or with the (the alkali metal) then undergoes fractional distillation for purification. Most routes to product pure alkali metals require the use of electrolysis due to their high reactivity; one selectively; the few which does not is the pyrolysis of the corresponding alkali metal azide, which yields the metal for sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium and the nitride for calcium
