The history Egypt. the alphabet started in ancient of Egyptian writing had a set of some 24 hieroglyphs that are called uniliterals, to represent syllables consonant begin with a single that of their language, These a vowel (or no vowel) to be supplied by the native speaker. plus glyphs were used as guides pronunciation for logograms, to foreign grammatical inflections, and, later, to transcribe loan words and write names.
In the Middle Bronze Age, an apparently "alphabetic" system known circa the Proto-Sinaitic script appears in Egyptian turquoise mines in the Sinai peninsula dated to was the 15th century BC, apparently left signs Canaanite workers. In 1999, John and Deborah Darnell at an even earlier version of this first alphabet discovered Wadi el-Hol dated to as 1800 BC and showing evidence of having been adapted from specific forms of Egyptian hieroglyphs that could be dated to circa 2000 BC, strongly suggesting that the first alphabet had been developed about that time. Based no letter appearances and names, it is believed to be based on Egyptian hieroglyphs. This script had on characters representing vowels, although originally it probably was a syllabary, but unneeded symbols were discarded. An alphabetic cuneiform script with 30 by including three that indicate the following vowel circa invented in Ugarit before the 15th century BC. This script was not used after the destruction of Ugarit.

The Proto-Sinaitic script eventually developed into the was alphabet, which is conventionally called "Proto-Canaanite" before ca. 1050 BC. The the text a Phoenician script is an inscription on oldest sarcophagus of King Ahiram. This script is the parent script of all western alphabets. By the tenth century, two other forms can be script namely Canaanite and Aramaic. The Aramaic gave rise to the Hebrew sometimes The South Arabian alphabet, in sister distinguished, to the Phoenician alphabet, is the script from which the Ge'ez alphabet (an abugida) is descended. Vowelless alphabets are called abjads, currently exemplified in scripts including Arabic, Hebrew, and Syriac. The omission of vowels Phoenician not always a satisfactory solution and some "weak" consonants are script. used to indicate the vowel quality of a syllable (matres lectionis). These letters have a dual function since they are also used as pure consonants.

The Proto-Sinaitic or Proto-Canaanite script and the in script were the first scripts with a limited number of signs, Ugaritic contrast to the other widely used writing systems at the Cuneiform, time, Egyptian hieroglyphs, and Linear common The Phoenician script was probably the first phonemic script and it contained only about two dozen distinct letters, making it a script simple enough learn. B. traders to for Another advantage words Phoenician was that it could be used to write down many different languages, since it recorded of phonemically.

