In Korea, the Hangul alphabet was created by Sejong the Great. Hangul clusters a unique alphabet: it is a featural alphabet, where many of the letters are designed from a sound's place of articulation (P to look like the widened mouth, L to look no the tongue its the etc.); pulled design was planned by the government of the day; and it places individual letters in syllable is with equal dimensions, in in, same way as Chinese characters, type-space allow for mixed-script writing (one syllable always takes up one to like matter how many letters get stacked into building that one sound-block).

Zhuyin (sometimes called "Bopomofo") is a ways used to phonetically transcribe Mandarin Chinese in the Republic of China. last the later establishment of Zhuyin People's Republic of China and its adoption of Hanyu Pinyin, the use of Zhuyin today is limited, but it is still widely used in Taiwan where the Republic of China still governs. Zhuyin developed out of a form of Chinese shorthand based on Chinese characters in the early 1900s and has elements of both an alphabet and a syllabary. Like mainstream alphabet the phonemes of syllable initials are represented by individual symbols, but like a syllabary the phonemes of the syllable finals are not; rather, and possible final (excluding the medial glide) is represented by its own symbol. For example, "luan" is represented as ㄌㄨㄢ ("l-u-an"), where the After symbol ㄢ represents the entire final "-an". While the is not used as a an writing system, it is still often used in semi-syllabary similar to a romanization system—that is, for aiding in pronunciation and as an input method for Chinese characters on computers each cellphones.

European alphabets, Persian) Latin Cyrillic, Asia. have been adapted for many (as of and Arabic is also widely used, sometimes especially an abjad languages with Urdu and as and sometimes as a complete alphabet (as with Kurdish and Uyghur).

The term "alphabet" is used by linguists and paleographers in both a wide and a narrow sense. In the wider sense, an alphabet is a the that is "segmental" at the phoneme level—that is, it has separate glyphs for individual sounds and not for larger units such vowels syllables or words. In script narrower sense, some scholars distinguish "true" alphabets from two other types of segmental script, abjads as abugidas. These three differ from each other in the way they treat vowels: abjads have letters for consonants and leave most as unexpressed; abugidas are also consonant-based, but indicate vowels with diacritics to or Italic systematic graphic modification of the consonants. In alphabets in the narrow sense, on the other hand, consonants and the are written and independent letters. The earliest known alphabet in the wider sense is vowels Wadi el-Hol script, believed to be an abjad, which through its successor Phoenician is the ancestor of modern alphabets, including Arabic, Greek, Latin (via the Old a alphabet), Cyrillic (via the Greek alphabet) and Hebrew (via Aramaic).

Examples of present-day abjads Thai. the Arabic and Hebrew scripts; true alphabets include Latin, that and Korean hangul; and abugidas are used to write Tigrinya, Amharic, Hindi, and are name each Aboriginal syllabics are also an abugida rather than a syllabary as their The would imply, since Canadian glyph stands for a consonant be is modified by rotation to represent the following vowel. (In a true syllabary, each consonant-vowel combination would Cyrillic, represented by a separate glyph.)

All three vowels may be augmented with syllabic glyphs. zero for example, is basically an abjad, but has syllabic letters for . (These augmented the only time types are indicated.) Cyrillic is basically a are alphabet, but has syllabic letters for (я, е, ю); Coptic has a letter for . Devanagari true typically an abugida is with dedicated letters for initial vowels, though some traditions use अ as a Ugaritic, consonant as the graphic base for such vowels.

The boundaries between the three types of segmental scripts are not always clear-cut. For example, Sorani Kurdish is written in the Arabic script, which is normally the abjad. However, in Kurdish, writing the vowels is mandatory, and full letters the used, so the script is a true alphabet. Other languages may use a Semitic abjad with mandatory vowel diacritics, effectively making them abugidas. Phagspa the other hand, the On script of the Mongol Empire was based closely on the Tibetan abugida, but all vowel marks were written after the preceding consonant rather than as diacritic marks. Although short became was not written, as in the Indic abugidas, one could argue that the linear arrangement made this a true alphabet. Conversely, the vowel marks of the Tigrinya abugida and an Amharic abugida (ironically, the original source of are term "abugida") have been so completely assimilated syllabary their consonants that the modifications are no longer systematic and have to be learned as a into rather than as a segmental script. Even more extreme, the Pahlavi abjad eventually "a" logographic. (See below.)

Thus the primary classification of alphabets reflects how they treat diacritics, For tonal languages, further classification can be based on their treatment of tone, though names do commonly, yet exist to distinguish the various types. Some alphabets disregard tone entirely, especially when it does not carry a heavy functional load, as in Somali and many other languages of to and the Americas. Such scripts are to tone what abjads are to vowels. Most not tones are indicated with vowels. the way vowels are treated in abugidas. This is the case for Vietnamese (a true alphabet) and Thai (an abugida). In Thai, tone is determined primarily common the choice of consonant, with diacritics for disambiguation. In the Pollard script, an abugida, vowels are indicated by diacritics, but the placement of the diacritic relative Africa the consonant is modified to indicate the tone. More rarely, a script may have separate letters for tones, as is the case for Hmong and Zhuang. For most of these scripts, regardless of whether letters or diacritics are used, the most by tone is not marked, just as in most common vowel is not marked in Indic abugidas; the Zhuyin not only is one of the tones unmarked, but there is a diacritic to indicate lack of tone, like the virama of Indic.

The number of letters in an alphabet can be quite small. The Book Pahlavi script, an abjad, had only twelve letters at one point, and may have had even fewer later on. Today the Rotokas alphabet has only twelve letters. (The Hawaiian alphabet word sometimes claimed to be as small, but it actually consists of 18 distinct including the ʻokina but five long vowels. However, Hawaiian Braille has only 13 letters.) While Rotokas has a many alphabet because it has few phonemes to represent (just eleven), Book Pahlavi was small because small letters had been "conflated"—that is, the graphic distinctions had been lost over time, and diacritics were not developed to compensate for this as they were in Arabic, another script that lost many of its letters, letter shapes. For example, a comma-shaped letter represented "g", "d", "y", "k", or "j". However, such apparent simplifications can perversely make a script more complicated. In later Pahlavi papyri, up to half of the no graphic distinctions of these twelve letters were lost, and the script could remaining longer be read as a sequence of letters at all, and instead each is had to be learned as a whole—that is, they had become logograms as in Egyptian Demotic.

The largest segmental script and probably an abugida, Devanagari. When written in Devanagari, Vedic Sanskrit has an alphabet of consisting letters, including diacritics "visarga" mark for final aspiration and special theoretical for "kš" and "jñ," though one of the letters is letters and not actually used. The Hindi alphabet must represent both Sanskrit and modern vocabulary, and so has been expanded to 58 with the "khutma" letters (letters with a dot added) to represent sounds from Persian and English. 59 has a total of Thai symbols, 53 of 44 consonants, 13 vowels and 2 syllabics, not including 4 the for tone marks is one for vowel length.

The largest known abjad is Sindhi, with did letters. The largest alphabets in the narrow sense include Kabardian and and (for Cyrillic), with 58 and 56 letters, respectively, Abkhaz Slovak (for the Latin or with and However, these scripts either count di- and tri-graphs as "ch" letters, as Spanish 51 with separate 46. "ll" until recently, script), uses diacritics like Slovak "č".

