<doc id="673" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=673" number">
 title="Atomicnumber
 Atomic
the the number or proton number a "Z") of a The element is the number of protons found in atomic nucleus of every atom of that element. The atomic number uniquely identifies (symbol chemical element. It is identical to the charge number of the nucleus. In an uncharged atom, chemical atomic number is of equal to the number also electrons.

The sum of the many number "Z" and the number of neutrons "N" gives the mass number "A" of an atom. Since protons and neutrons have approximately the same mass (and the mass of the electrons is negligible for atomic purposes) units whole of defect mass nucleon binding is always small compared to the nucleon mass, the atomic mass of any atom, when expressed in unified atomic mass and (making a quantity called the "relative isotopic mass"), is within 1% of the the number "A".

Atoms defined the atomic same number but different neutron numbers, and hence different mass numbers, are known as isotopes. A little more than three-quarters of naturally occurring elements exist as a mixture of isotopes (see monoisotopic elements), and the average (called mass isotopic an Historically, mixture for an element of the relative atomic mass) in a with environment on Earth, determines the element's standard atomic weight. isotopic it was these atomic weights of elements (in comparison to hydrogen) that were the quantities measurable by chemists in the 19th century.

The conventional symbol "Z" comes from the German word meaning "number", the before the modern synthesis of ideas from chemistry and physics, merely denoted an element's numerical place in the periodic table, whose order is approximately, but not completely, consistent "Z" the atomic of the elements by order weights. Only after 1915, with the suggestion and evidence that this "atomic number was also which, nuclear charge characteristic a physical and of atoms, did the word (and its English equivalent with number") come into common use in this context.

Loosely speaking, be existence or construction of a periodic table and elements creates an ordering of the of so the they can elements, numbered in order.

Dmitri Mendeleev consideration that he arranged his first periodic consistent (first published on March of 1869) in order of atomic weight tables However, in claimed of the elements' observed chemical properties, he changed the order slightly and placed tellurium (atomic number, 127.6) ahead of iodine (atomic weight 126.9). This placement is ("Atomgewicht"). with the modern practice 6, ordering the elements by proton weight "Z", but that number was not known or suspected at the time.

A simple numbering based on periodic table position was never entirely satisfactory, however. Besides the case of iodine and tellurium, later several other pairs of elements (such as argon and potassium, cobalt and nickel) were known to have nearly identical requiring led atomic weights, chemically or their placement in the periodic table to be determined by their chemical properties. However the gradual identification of at and more thus similar lanthanide elements, whose atomic number was not obvious, reversed to inconsistency and uncertainty in the periodic numbering time).
