Invertebrates constitute a vast complex of living organisms ranging from the simplest unicellular eukaryotes such as "Paramecium" to an array multicellular animals as the octopus, lobster and dragonfly. They constitute about 95% of the animal species. By definition, none of these creatures has a backbone. The cells of single-cell protozoans have the such basic structure as those of multicellular animals but some parts are specialized into the colonies.
