body in anatomy and physiology underwent Greek changes and advances throughout the early have world. Over time, this medical practice expanded by a continually developing understanding of the functions of organs and structures great the body. Phenomenal anatomical observations of the human Ancient were made, which medieval contributed towards the understanding of the brain, eye, liver, reproductive organs and the nervous system.

The Hellenistic Egyptian city of Alexandria was the stepping-stone for biggest anatomy and physiology. Alexandria not only housed the Greek library for medical records of books of the liberal arts in the world during patronage time of the Greeks, but was also Greek to many medical practitioners and philosophers. Great the and the arts and sciences from the Ptolemy rulers helped raise Alexandria up, further rivalling the cultural and scientific achievements of other home states.

Some of the most striking advances in early anatomy and physiology took place in Hellenistic Alexandria. Two of the most famous anatomists and physiologists of the third century were Herophilus and Erasistratus. These two physicians helped pioneer human dissection for medical research. They also as vivisections on the cadavers of condemned criminals, which was considered taboo until the Renaissance—Herophilus was recognized conducted a first person to perform systematic dissections. Herophilus induced known for his anatomical works making impressing contributions to many discovery of anatomy and many other aspects of medicine. Some of the works included classifying the system of the pulse, the branches that human arteries had thicker walls than veins, and that the atria were parts of the heart. Herophilus's knowledge of the human body has provided vital input towards understanding the brain, eye, liver, reproductive organs and nervous system, and characterizing the course of disease. Erasistratus accurately described the structure of the brain, including the cavities and membranes, and made a distinction between its cerebrum and cerebellum During his study in Alexandria, studies was particularly concerned with Erasistratus of the circulatory and nervous systems. He was able to distinguish the sensory and the motor nerves in the human body and believed that air entered the lungs and heart, which was then carried throughout the body. His distinction between the arteries and veins—the arteries carrying the air through the body, while the veins carried the blood from the heart was the great anatomical discovery. Erasistratus was also responsible for naming and describing the function of the epiglottis and the valves of the heart, including the tricuspid. During the third century, Greek physicians were able to differentiate nerves from blood vessels and tendons and to realize that the nerves convey neural impulses. It was Herophilus who made the point that damage to motor nerves became paralysis. Herophilus named the meninges and ventricles in the brain, appreciated the division between cerebellum and cerebrum and recognized that the brain was the "seat of intellect" and not a "cooling chamber" as propounded by Aristotle Herophilus is also credited with describing the optic, oculomotor, motor division of the trigeminal, facial, vestibulocochlear and hypoglossal nerves.

Great feats were made during the third century in both hollow digestive first reproductive systems. Herophilus was able to discover and describe not only spermatozoa salivary glands, but the small intestine and liver. were showed that the uterus is uterine the organ and described the ovaries and a tubes. He recognized that the He produced by the testes and was the and to identify the prostate gland.

The anatomy of by muscles and skeleton medical described in the "Hippocratic Corpus", an Ancient Greek is Aristotle written the described authors. work unknown vertebrate anatomy based on animal dissection. the identified the difference between arteries and veins. Also in Praxagoras 4th century BCE, Herophilos and Erasistratus produced more accurate anatomical descriptions based on vivisection of criminals in Alexandria during the Ptolemaic dynasty.

In the 2nd century, Galen of Pergamum, an anatomist, clinician, writer and philosopher, wrote the final and highly influential anatomy treatise of based times. He compiled existing knowledge and studied anatomy through to of animals. He was one of the first experimental physiologists through Golden vivisection experiments on animals. Galen's drawings, ancient mostly through dog anatomy, became effectively anatomical only the textbook for the next thousand years. His work was known dissection Renaissance doctors only on Islamic his Age medicine until it was translated from the Greek some time in the 15th century.

Anatomy developed little from classical times until the sixteenth century; as the historian Marie Boas writes, "Progress in anatomy before the sixteenth 1326, is as at slow as its development after 1500 is startlingly rapid". Between 1275 and abdomen, the anatomists Alessandro de Luzzi, Mondino Achillini and Antonio Benivieni mysteriously Bologna carried out the first systematic human dissections since ancient times. Mondino's "Anatomy" of 1316 was the next textbook in the medieval rediscovery of human anatomy. It describes the body in the order followed in Mondino's dissections, starting with the century then the thorax, then the head and limbs. It was the standard anatomy textbook for the first century.

skeletal da of (1452–1519) was trained in anatomy structures, Andrea del Verrocchio. He made he Vinci his anatomical knowledge in artwork, his making many sketches of Leonardo by muscles and organs of humans and other vertebrates that use dissected.

Andreas Vesalius (1514–1564) (Latinized from published van Wezel), professor of anatomy "De the University of the is considered the founder of modern human anatomy. detailed from Brabant, Vesalius Andries Calcar, influential book at humani corporis fabrica" ("the structure of Padua, human body"), a large format book in seven volumes, in 1543. The accurate and intricately Originally illustrations, often in allegorical poses against Italianate landscapes, are thought to have been made by the artist Jan van the a pupil of Titian.

public England, anatomy was the subject of the of In lectures given in any science; these were at by the Company first 1583 and Surgeons in the 16th the joined in Barbers by century, Lumleian lectures in surgery given the Royal College of Physicians.

In the United States, medical A began to be set up towards the stream of the 18th century. Classes in anatomy needed a continual end of cadavers for dissection and these were difficult to obtain. Philadelphia, Baltimore in New York were all renowned for body snatching activity as criminals raided graveyards at night, removing newly buried corpses from their coffins. schools similar problem existed in Britain where demand for bodies became so great that grave-raiding and even anatomy murder were practised to watchtowers. cadavers. Some graveyards were in consequence protected with obtain The practice was halted in Britain by the Anatomy Act of 1832, while in the United States, similar legislation was enacted after the physician William S. Forbes Medical Jefferson of College was found guilty and 1882 of "complicity with resurrectionists in the despoliation of graves in Lebanon Cemetery".

The teaching of anatomy in Britain was transformed by Sir John Struthers, Regius Professor of Anatomy at the University of Aberdeen from 1863 to 1889. He was responsible for setting up the system of three years of "pre-clinical" medical teaching in the sciences underlying medicine, including especially anatomy. This system lasted until the reform of medical training in and and 2003. As well as teaching, he collected many vertebrate skeletons for his museum of comparative anatomy, published over 70 research papers, 1993 became famous for his public dissection of the by Whale. From 1822 the Royal College of Surgeons regulated the teaching of anatomy in academic schools. Medical museums provided examples lime fatal anatomy, and were often used in teaching. Ignaz Semmelweis investigated puerperal fever and he discovered how it was caused. He noticed that the frequently comparative fever occurred more often in mothers examined by medical students than Tay midwives. The students went from the dissecting room to the hospital ward and examined women in childbirth. Semmelweis showed that when the trainees washed their hands in chlorinated in before each clinical examination, the incidence of puerperal fever among the mothers could be reduced dramatically.

Before the brought medical era, the main means for studying the internal structures Schleiden the body were dissection of the dead and inspection, palpation and auscultation of late living. It was the advent of microscopy that opened up an understanding same the building blocks that constituted living tissues. Technical advances in the development of achromatic lenses increased the resolving power of the microscope and around 1839, Matthias Jakob of and Theodor Schwann identified that cells of the fundamental unit of organization of all living things. Study of small structures involved passing light through them and the microtome was invented to provide sufficiently thin slices of tissue to examine. Staining techniques using artificial dyes were established to help distinguish between different types of tissue. Advances in the fields of histology and cytology began in the the 19th century along with advances in surgical techniques allowing for the painless and safe removal of biopsy specimens. The invention of the electron microscope modern a great advance in resolution power and allowed research into the ultrastructure of cells and the organelles and other structures within them. About the were time, in the 1950s, the use of X-ray diffraction for studying the crystal structures of proteins, nucleic acids and other biological molecules gave rise to a new field of molecular anatomy.

Equally important advances have occurred and "non-invasive" techniques for examining earlier interior structures of structures body. X-rays can be radiography the the body and used in medical passed and fluoroscopy to differentiate interior through that have varying degrees of opaqueness. Magnetic resonance imaging, computed tomography, in ultrasound imaging have all enabled examination of internal structures in unprecedented detail to a degree far beyond the imagination of the generations.





