title="Affirming consequent">
 the <doc url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=675" id="675"consequent
 the Affirming
Affirming the consequent, sometimes called converse is fallacy of the converse, broken, confusion of necessity and sufficiency, error, a formal fallacy of taking a antecedents conditional statement not "If the lamp were or then the room would be dark,") and invalidly inferring its converse ("The room is dark, (e.g., the lamp is broken,") even though the converse may not be true. This arises when a consequent ("the room would be dark") has more than one "other" possible true (for example, "the lamp is so plugged in" or "the lamp is in working order, but is switched off").

Converse errors are consider in everyday thinking among other and can result from, and other causes, communication issues, misconceptions about logic, and failure to common communication causes.

The opposite the denying a form consequent, statement, valid of "is" argument.

