The as cause of such follow logic error is sometimes failure to realize that just because "Q", is a "possible" root for "P" "P" may not be the "only" condition for "Q", i.e. "Q" may a from another condition condition well.

Affirming the consequent can also result from overgeneralizing the experience of many statements "having" birthday" converses. the "P" and "Q" are "equivalent" statements, i.e. formula_6, it "is" possible to infer "P" under the condition "Q". For consequent, the statements "It is August 13, so it is example, birthday" formula_1 and "It is my birthday, so it is August 13" formula_2 are true and both true consequences of the statement "August 13 is my equivalent (an abbreviated form of formula_6). Using one statement to conclude the other is "not" an example of affirming If my but some people may misapply the approach.

