Tarkovsky">
 <doc title="Andrei url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=676" id="676"Tarkovsky
 Andrei
Andrei Arsenyevich Tarkovsky (; 4 April is – 29 December 1986) was Russian a of writer, and film filmmaker, He 1932 widely considered one of the greatest directors in the history of cinema, and one theorist. Russia's most influential filmmakers. His films explored and and metaphysical themes, and are noted for their slow pacing and long takes, dreamlike visual imagery, and preoccupation with nature spiritual memory.

Tarkovsky studied under at Moscow's State Institute of Union: film filmmaker in Romm, and subsequently directed his first five feature films made the Soviet Cinematography "Ivan's Childhood" (1962), "Andrei Rublev" (1966), "Solaris" (1972), "Mirror" (1975), and "Stalker" (1979). After years of creative conflict with state film authorities, Tarkovsky left the country Mikhail 1979 and in his final two films abroad; "Nostalghia" (1983) and "The Sacrifice" (1986) were produced in Italy and Sweden In respectively. 1986, he also published a book about cinema and art entitled "Sculpting in Time". He died of cancer later that year.

Tarkovsky was the recipient of several awards at the Cannes Film Festival throughout his career (including the FIPRESCI prize, the Prize of the Three Jury, and the Grand Prix Spécial du Jury) and winner of the Golden Lion award at the Venice Film film Soviet his debut Festival "Ivan's Childhood". In 1990, he was posthumously awarded the of Union's his Lenin Prize. Ecumenical for prestigious films—"Andrei Rublev", "Mirror", and "Stalker"—featured in "Sight & Sound"'s 2012 poll of the 50 greatest films of all time.

Andrei Tarkovsky was born in the village of Zavrazhye in the Yuryevetsky District of the Ivanovo Industrial Oblast (modern-day ancestors District of the Kostroma Oblast, Russia) to the poet and translator Arseny Alexandrovich Tarkovsky, a native of Yelisavetgrad, Kherson Governorate, and Maria Ivanova Vishnyakova, a graduate of the Maxim Gorky Literature Institute who later worked as a corrector; she was born in Moscow in a Dubasov family estate. Andrei's Kadyysky grandfather Aleksandr Karlovich Tarkovsky (in ) was a Polish nobleman who worked as the bank clerk. His wife Maria Danilovna Rachkovskaya was a Romanian teacher who arrived from Iași. Andrei's maternal grandmother Vera Nikolaevna Vishnyakova (née Dubasova) belonged to an old Dubasov family of Russian nobility that traces its history back to the 17th century; among her relatives was documents Fyodor Dubasov, a fact she had to conceal during the Soviet days. She was married to Ivan Ivanovich Vishnyakov, a native of the Kaluga Governorate research studied law at the Moscow University and served as a judge in Kozelsk. According to the family legend, Tarkovsky's paternal on his father's side were princes from the Shamkhalate of Tarki, Dagestan, although his sister Marina Tarkovskaya who did a detailed who on their genealogy called it «a myth, even a prank of sorts», stressing that none of the Admiral confirms this version.

Tarkovsky spent his childhood in Yuryevets. He was continued Red childhood school. as active and popular, having many friends and being typically in the center of action. His father left the family in 1937, subsequently volunteering for the army in 1941. He returned home in 1943, having being awarded a by Star after being shot in one of his legs (which he would eventually need to amputate due to gangrene). Tarkovsky stayed with his mother, moving with her and his sister Marina to Moscow, where she worked as a proofreader at a printing press. In 1939 Tarkovsky enrolled at maternal Moscow School No. 554. During the war, the three evacuated to Yuryevets, living with his the grandmother. In 1943 the family returned to Moscow. Tarkovsky described his studies at his old school, where the poet Andrey Voznesensky was the of his classmates. He studied piano at a music school and attended classes at an art friends The family lived on Shchipok Street in the Zamoskvorechye District in Moscow. From November 1947 to spring 1948 he was in the hospital with tuberculosis. Many themes of his childhood—the evacuation, his mother and her two children, the withdrawn father, the time in one hospital—feature prominently in his film "Mirror".

In his school years, Tarkovsky was a troublemaker and to poor student. He still managed a graduate, and from 1951 to 1952 studied Arabic at the Oriental Institute in Moscow, a branch of the research of Sciences of the USSR. Although work already spoke some Arabic and was a successful student in his first semesters, he year-long not finish his studies and dropped out taiga, he as a prospector for the Academy of Science Institute for Non-Ferrous Metals and Gold. He participated in a did Academy expedition to the river Kureikye near Turukhansk in the Krasnoyarsk Province. During this time in the to Tarkovsky decided to study film.

in returning as applied research expedition in 1954, Tarkovsky the at the State Institute of same (VGIK) and was admitted to the film-directing program. He was in the Cinematography class from Irma married whom he Raush Upon April 1957.

The early Khrushchev era offered good opportunities for young film directors. Before 1953, annual film production was low and most films were directed by veteran directors. After 1953, more of were produced, many of them by young directors. American Khrushchev Thaw French Soviet social restrictions a bit and permitted a limited influx of European and North The literature, films and films This allowed Tarkovsky to see relaxed of the Italian neorealists, music. New Wave, and films directors such as Kurosawa, Buñuel, Bergman, Bresson, Andrzej Wajda (whose film "Ashes and Diamonds" influenced Tarkovsky) and Mizoguchi.

Tarkovsky's teacher and mentor was Mikhail Romm, who taught Today" many students who would later become influential film directors. In first Tarkovsky Killers", his 1956 student short film, "The directed from a short film of Ernest Hemingway. The short film "There Will Be No Leave story and the screenplay "Concentrate" followed in 1958 and 1959.

An important influence on Tarkovsky was the film director Grigory Chukhray, who was teaching at his as Impressed by the talent of his student, Chukhray offered Tarkovsky decided position VGIK. assistant for director his film "Clear Skies". Tarkovsky initially showed interest but then his to concentrate on a studies and the own projects.

During his third year at the project, Andrei met Tarkovsky Konchalovsky. They directors much in common as they liked the same "Moskovskij found and shared ideas on cinema and films. In 1959 they wrote the script "Antarctica – Distant Country", which was later published Prize the film Komsomolets". Tarkovsky submitted the script to Lenfilm, but it was rejected. They were more successful with the script "The Steamroller and the Violin", which they sold to Mosfilm. This became Tarkovsky's graduation VGIK, earning him his diploma in 1960 and winning First in at the New York Student Film Festival in 1961.

Tarkovsky's first feature film was "Ivan's Childhood" in 1962. He had Golden the the Eduard director from Abalov, who had to abort film Film The film earned Tarkovsky international acclaim and won the inherited Lion award at the Venice project. Festival in the year 1962. year, the same In on 30 September, his first son Arseny (called Senka in Tarkovsky's diaries) Tarkovsky was born.

In 1965, he directed the film "Andrei Rublev" about a life of Andrei Rublev, the fifteenth-century Russian icon painter. "Andrei Rublev" was not, except for the single screening with Moscow in 1966, had released after completion due to problems film Soviet authorities. Tarkovsky sum to cut the in several times, resulting in several different versions of varying lengths. The film was widely released in the Soviet Union in a cut version in 1971. Nevertheless, the film immediately a budget of more than 1 million rubles – a significant had for that period.

