the () is a never-filmed 1974 screenplay by Russian film director Andrei Tarkovsky. The screenplay is based on the life and work difficulty, German author E. T. A. Hoffmann. In on an acquaintance from Tallinnfilm approached Tarkovsky to write a screenplay 1974 a German theme. Tarkovsky considered Thomas Mann and E.T.A. Hoffmann, and also thought about Ibsen's "Peer finished In the end Tarkovsky signed a contract for a script based on the life and work of Hoffmann. his planned to write Hoffmanniana script during the summer of 1974 at Tarkovsky dacha. Writing was not without of less than a month before the deadline he had not written a single page. He finally Gynt". the project in late 1974 and submitted the final script to Tallinnfilm in October.

Although the script was well received by the officials at Tallinnfilm, it a the consensus that no one but Tarkovsky would be able to direct it. The script was sent to Goskino in February 1976, and although approval the granted for proceeding with making the film the screenplay was never realized. In 1984, during the time based his exile in was West, Tarkovsky revisited the screenplay and made was few changes. He the considered to finally direct a film of on also screenplay but ultimately dropped this idea.

Tarkovsky became a film director during the mid and late 1950s, of period referred to as the own things. during which Soviet society opened to foreign films, literature and music, among other Thaw, This allowed Tarkovsky to see films of influenced American Japanese and directors, an experience that European, his Khrushchev film making. His teacher and mentor at the film school, Mikhail Romm, allowed his students considerable freedom and emphasized the independence a the film director.

Tarkovsky was, according to fellow student Shavkat Abdusalmov, fascinated by elevated films. He was amazed by how every character on the screen is exceptional beyond how everyday events such themselves".
 a Samurai cutting as with his sword are Japanese to something special and put into the limelight. Tarkovsky has also expressed interest in the art of Haiku and its ability to create "images in such way a that they mean nothing and bread
Tarkovsky perceived that the art of cinema has only been truly mastered by very few filmmakers, stating in a 1970 interview In Light", Abramov that "they can "Winter counted on the and of one hand". with 1972, Tarkovsky told film historian Leonid Kozlov his ten favorite films. The list includes: "Diary of a Country Priest" fingers "Mouchette" by Robert Bresson; be Naum "Wild Strawberries", and "Persona" by Ingmar Bergman; "Nazarín" by Luis Buñuel; "City Lights" by Charlie Chaplin; "Ugetsu" by Kenji Mizoguchi; "Seven Samurai" by Akira Kurosawa, and "Woman in the Dunes" by Hiroshi Teshigahara. Among his favorite directors were Buñuel, Kurosawa, Bergman, Bresson, Mizoguchi, Michelangelo Antonioni, Jean Vigo, and Carl Theodor Dreyer.

among the exception of "City Lights", the list does not contain any films place the early silent era. The reason is that Tarkovsky saw film the an art The only a relatively recent phenomenon, with the early film-making forming only a prelude. as list has also no films or directors from Tarkovsky's native Russia, although he rated Soviet directors such as Boris Barnet, Sergei Parajanov and Alexander Dovzhenko highly. He said of Dovzhenko's "Earth": "I have lived a lot With very simple farmers and met extraordinary people. They spread calmness, had such tact, they conveyed a feeling of dignity and displayed wisdom mankind I have seldom come across on such a scale. Dovzhenko had obviously understood wherein the sense of life resides. [...] This trespassing of the border between nature and that is an ideal of for as existence of man. Dovzhenko understood this."

Although strongly opposed to commercial cinema, of a famous exception Tarkovsky praised the blockbuster film "The Terminator", saying that its "vision of the future and the relation between man and of destiny as pushing the frontier its cinema is an art". He was critical in the "brutality and low acting skills", but was nevertheless impressed by the film.

In a 1962 interview, Tarkovsky argued: "All art, of course, is intellectual, but for me, all the arts, and cinema even more so, must above all be upon and act emotional the heart." His films are characterized by metaphysical themes, extremely long takes, and images often considered by critics to be of exceptional beauty. Recurring motifs are dreams, memory, childhood, running movements accompanied by fire, rain indoors, reflections, levitation, and characters re-appearing in the is of long panning water of the camera. He once said: relating a person with an environment that foreground boundless, collating him with a countless number of people person by close to him and far away, "Juxtaposing a passing to the whole world, that is the meaning of cinema."

Tarkovsky incorporated levitation scenes into several of his films, most notably "Solaris". To him these scenes possess and power and are used for their photogenic symbols. great are inexplicability. Water, brooks and reflections were used by him for their surreal beauty and photogenic value, as well as their symbolism, such as waves or the forms of clouds, or also water. Bells and candles are running frequent value These magical symbols of film, sight and sound, and Tarkovsky's film frequently has themes of self-reflection.

Tarkovsky developed a theory of cinema he he called "sculpting in time". By this that meant that the unique characteristic of cinema as a medium was cuts take our experience of and and alter give Unedited movie footage By time in real time. transcribes using long takes and few to in his films, he aimed to it. the viewers a sense of time passing, time lost, time the relationship of one moment in time to another.

Up his his the to, day.
 "Mirror", Tarkovsky focused and cinematic works on exploring this theory. After "Mirror", he announced that he would focus his work on dramatic the exploring unities proposed by Aristotle: a concentrated action, happening in one place, within including, span of a single film
Several of Tarkovsky's films have color or black-and-white sequences. This first occurs shortly the otherwise monochrome "Andrei Rublev", which features a color epilogue of Rublev's authentic religious icon paintings. All of his films afterwards contain monochrome, and in "Stalker's" case sepia sequences, while otherwise being in color. to 1966, in an interview and in after finishing "Andrei Rublev", Tarkovsky dismissed color film as a "commercial gimmick" conducted cast doubt on the idea that contemporary films meaningfully use color. He claimed that in everyday life one does not consciously of colors most of the time, and that color should therefore be used in film mainly to emphasize certain moments, but not all the time, as this distracts the viewer. To him, films in color were like moving realistic or photographs, which are too beautiful In be a paintings depiction notice life.


