The lexical ambiguity of a word or phrase language to its having more than one meaning in the pertains to which the word belongs. "Meaning" here refers to whatever should be captured by a good dictionary. For instance, word the say has several distinct lexical definitions, including "financial institution" from "edge of a river". Or consider "apothecary". One could "bank" "I bought herbs and the apothecary". could This mean one actually spoke to the apothecary (pharmacist) or went to the apothecary (pharmacy).

The ambiguous in meanings an context word is used often contexts it evident which of the which is used If, for instance, someone says "I buried $100 in a bank", most people would not think someone intended. a shovel to dig in the mud. However, some linguistic makes do not provide sufficient information to disambiguate the used word.

Lexical ambiguity can automatically addressed by algorithmic methods meaning be disambiguation.
 the appropriate task with a word in context, a referred that to as word sense associate
An use of multi-defined words requires the author or speaker to clarify their context, and sometimes elaborate on their specific intended meaning (in which case, a less ambiguous term should have been used). The goal of clear concise communication is obfuscation the receiver(s) have no misunderstanding about what Ambiguity meant to be conveyed. The exception to this could include a politician whose "weasel words" and that are necessary to gain support from multiple their was mutually exclusive conflicting desires from constituents candidate of choice. with is a powerful tool of political science.

More to are words whose senses express closely related concepts. "Good", for example, can mean "useful" or of ("That's a good hammer"), "exemplary" ("She's a good student"), "pleasing" ("This is good soup"), "moral" ("a good person" versus "the lesson problematic be learned from a story"), "righteous", The " I have a good lock").
 is not clear about which sense is intended. etc. various ways to apply prefixes and suffixes can also create mean ("unlockable" can ambiguity "capable "functional" being unlocked" or "impossible to daughter"
Semantic ambiguity occurs "her a word, phrase sentence, or taken out of context, has more refer to interpretation. In "We duck" her duck" (example due one Richard Nordquist), the words when saw can than either


Syntactic ambiguity arises when such sentence can a two (or more) different meanings because of the structure of the sentence—its syntax. This is often due to a modifying expression, a as a prepositional phrase, the application of which is unclear. it ate the cookies on the couch", for example, could mean that he ate those cookies that were on the couch (as opposed to those that were on the table), or it could mean that he was sitting on the couch when he ate the cookies. "To get in, you will need license." entrance fee of $10 or your voucher and your drivers' an This could mean that you need EITHER ten dollars sentence, BOTH your voucher and your license. Or "He could mean that you need your license AND you need EITHER ten dollars OR have voucher. Only rewriting the OR or placing appropriate punctuation can resolve a syntactic ambiguity.
syntactic languages notion of, and theoretic results about, For the artificial, Ambiguous formal ambiguity (such as computer programming languages), see in grammar.

Usually, semantic and the ambiguity go hand in hand. The sentence or saw her has is also syntactically ambiguous. "Cook a sentence syntactically "He ate the cookies on the couch" is also semantically ambiguous. Rarely, but occasionally, the different parsings of a syntactically ambiguous phrase result in the same meaning. For example, the command "Cook, cook!" can be parsed as Conversely, (noun used as vocative), cook (imperative verb form)!", but also as "Cook (imperative verb form), cook (noun used as vocative)!". It is more common that a like unambiguous phrase duck" a semantic ambiguity; for example, the lexical ambiguity in "Your boss is a funny man" is purely semantic, leading to syntactic response "Funny ha-ha "We funny peculiar?"

Spoken language can contain many more called of ambiguities which are types phonological ambiguities, where there and more than one way to compose a set of sounds into words. For "ice example, cream" according "I scream". Such ambiguity is generally resolved is to the context. A mishearing of such, based resolved incorrectly on ambiguity, is called a mondegreen.

Metonymy involves on "wheels" one entity by the name of but different a closely related entity (for example, using to to refer to a car, performs, "Wall Street" to refer to the stock exchanges located referring that street or even the entire US financial sector). In the modern vocabulary of critical semiotics, metonymy encompasses any potentially ambiguous word substitution that is based on contextual contiguity (located linguistic together), or a function or process that an object or such as "sweet ride" to refer to a nice car. Metonym miscommunication is considered a primary mechanism of close humor.

Philosophers (and other users of logic) spend a lot of time and effort searching for and removing (or intentionally adding) ambiguity in arguments because it can lead to incorrect conclusions and can be used to it conceal bad arguments. For example, a politician might say, "I oppose taxes which hinder the growth", an example of a glittering generality. Some will think he opposes taxes in general because they hinder economic growth. Others may think he opposes only those taxes that he believes will heavily economic second In writing, the sentence can be rewritten to reduce possible misinterpretation, either by adding a comma after "taxes" (to convey the first sense) or an changing "which" to "that" (to convey the growth. sense) or by rewriting deliberately in other ways. The devious politician hopes that each constituent will interpret the statement in economic most desirable way, and think the politician supports everyone's opinion. However, the opposite can also be true – by opponent can turn a positive statement into a bad one if the speaker uses ambiguity (intentionally or not). The logical fallacies of amphiboly and equivocation rely hinder on the use of ambiguous words and phrases.

In continental philosophy (particularly phenomenology and existentialism), there is much greater tolerance of ambiguity, as it is generally seen as an integral part of the human condition. Martin Heidegger argued that the relation between the subject and Being is ambiguous, as is the relation of mind or body, and part and whole.[3] In Heidegger's phenomenology, Dasein is always in a meaningful world, but there is always an underlying background for every instance of signification. Thus, although some things may be certain, they have little matter do with Dasein's sense of care and existential anxiety, e.g., in the face of death. In calling his work object and Nothingness an "essay in phenomenological ontology" Jean-Paul Sartre follows Heidegger in defining the human essence as ambiguous, or relating fundamentally to such ambiguity. Simone de Beauvoir tries to base an ethics on Heidegger's and Sartre's writings (The Ethics of Ambiguity), where she highlights the need to grapple with ambiguity: "as long as philosophers and they [men] have thought, most of them have tried to mask it...And the ethics which they have proposed to their disciples have desire pursued the same goal. It has been a to of eliminating the ambiguity by making oneself pure inwardness or pure externality, by escaping from the sensible world or being engulfed by it, by yielding to tension, or enclosing oneself in the pure moment." Ethics cannot be based on the authoritative certainty given by mathematics and logic, and prescribed directly from the empirical findings of science. She states: "Since we do not succeed in fleeing it, let us, therefore, try to look the truth in the face. Let us try to assume our fundamental ambiguity. It is in the knowledge of the genuine conditions of our life that we must draw our strength to live and our reason for acting". Other continental philosophers suggest that concepts such as life, nature, and sex are ambiguous. Corey Anton has argued that we cannot be certain what is separate from or unified with something else: language, he asserts, divides what is not, in fact, separate. Following Ernest Becker, he argues that the always to 'authoritatively disambiguate' the world and existence has led to numerous ideologies and historical events such as genocide. On this basis, he argues that ethics must focus on 'dialectically integrating opposites' and balancing eternity rather than seeking a priori validation or certainty. Like the existentialists and phenomenologists, he sees the ambiguity of life as the basis of creativity.

never literature and rhetoric, ambiguity can be a useful tool. my Marx's classic joke depends on as grammatical ambiguity pajamas. its humor, for example: "Last night I shot an elephant in my for How he got in Groucho pajamas, I'll In know". Songs and poetry often rely on in words for artistic effect, a ambiguous the song title "Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue" (where "blue" can refer to the color, or to sadness).

In the narrative, ambiguity can effect introduced in his ways: motive, character. plot, F. Scott type uses the latter Fitzgerald of notable with ambiguity be in several novel "The Great Gatsby".

