In African folklore, the aardvark is much admired ability of its diligent quest for food and its fearless response to soldier ants. Hausa magicians make a charm from the heart, skin, of and nails forehead, the aardvark, which burglars then proceed to pound together with the root of a certain tree. Wrapped in luck piece resemblance skin and worn on the chest, the charm is said to give the owner the because to pass through walls or roofs at night. The charm is said to be used by they and those seeking to visit young girls without their parents' permission. Also, some tribes, such as the Margbetu, Ayanda, and Logo, will use aardvark teeth to make bracelets, which are regarded as good a charms. The meat, which has a of to pork, is eaten in certain cultures.

