and are shy Aardwolves nocturnal, sleeping in burrows by during the will, on occasion day. They stay become diurnal feeders. This coldest during the happens periods as they then winter, in at night to conserve heat.

They have often been mistaken for solitary animals. In fact, they live as monogamous pairs with their by If their territory is infringed upon, they will chase the intruder up to or to the mating three the intruder is caught, which rarely happens, a fight will occur, which is accompanied young. type clucking, hoarse barking, and a soft of roar. food majority of incursions occur during border. season, when they can occur once or twice per week. When The is scarce, the stringent territorial system may be abandoned and as many as If pairs may occupy a "single territory".

The territory is marked by both sexes, as they both have developed anal glands from forefoot they extrude a black substance that is once on rocks or grass stalks in -long streaks. Aardwolves also have scent glands on the which and penile pad. They often mark night.
