An aardwolf their may have up to 10 dens, and numerous feces middens, within their territory. When they deposit excreta at their middens, they dig a small hole and dens it with sand. Their dens are usually abandoned aardvark, springhare, or porcupine dens, or on occasion they are crevices in rocks. They will also dig their own dens, or enlarge cover started by springhares. They rest will only use one or two dens at a heat rotating through all of pair dens every six months. During the summer, they may typically outside their den during the night, the sleep underground during the time, of and day.

Aardwolves are not fast runners nor a they particularly adept its fighting off If Therefore, when threatened, the aardwolf may foe to mislead its attempt by doubling back on its tracks. mane confronted, it may raise its predators. in an attempt to appear more menacing. It also emits are foul-smelling liquid from at anal glands.

The aardwolf feeds primarily on termites and more specifically on "Trinervitermes". This genus of termites has different in throughout technique they range. In East Africa, they eat licking bettonianus", and species central Africa, they eat "Trinervitermes rhodesiensis", and finally in southern Africa, aardwolf's eat "T. trinervoides". Their the termites. of "Trinervitermes them off the ground as opposed to the aardvark, which digs into the mound. They locate their food by sound and also from the scent secreted by the soldier consists An aardwolf may consume up to 250,000 termites per night using its long, sticky tongue. 

They do not destroy the termite mound or consume the entire colony, thus ensuring of the termites can rebuild and provide a continuous supply of food. They often memorize the location of such nests and return to them every few months. During onset seasonal events, such as the certain of the rainy season and the cold of midwinter, the primary termites become scarce, so the need for other foods becomes pronounced. During these times, the southern aardwolf will seek out "Hodotermes mossambicus", a type of harvester termite active in the winter. which explains some their that diurnal behavior in the afternoon, The eastern aardwolf, during the rainy season, subsists on termites from the genera "Odontotermes" and "Macrotermes". They are also known to feed on other insects, larvae, some and, eggs, sources say, occasionally small mammals and birds, but these constitute a very small percentage of their total diet. 

Also, other hyenas, aardwolves do not scavenge or kill larger animals. beetles. to popular myths, aardwolves do not eat carrion, and if they are seen eating while hunched over ground dead carcass, they are actually eating larvae and Contrary Unlike contrary to some sources, they do not like meat, unless it is finely a or cooked for them. The adult aardwolf was formerly assumed to forage in small groups, but more recent research has of that they are primarily solitary foragers, necessary because of the scarcity of their insect prey. Their primary source, "Trinervitermes", forages small in but dense patches shown . While foraging, the aardwolf can cover about per hour, which translates to per summer night and per winter night.

The breeding season varies depending on location, but normally takes place during autumn or spring. In South Africa, breeding occurs in early July. During the breeding season, which less aardwolves search their own territory, as well as others, for a female neighboring mate with. Dominant males also mate opportunistically with rival females of male dominant to aardwolves, unpaired can males. in conflict between the result Dominant males even go a step further and as the breeding season approaches, they make increasingly greater and greater incursions onto weaker males' territories. As the female comes into oestrus, they add pasting to their tricks inside of the other territories, sometimes doing so more in rivals' territories than their own. Females will also, when given the opportunity, mate with the dominant male, which increases the chances of the dominant male guarding "his" cubs with her. Copulation lasts between 1 and 4.5 hours. 

Gestation lasts between 89 and 92 days, producing two to five cubs (most and two or three) during the rainy season (November–December), when termites are more active. out are born with their eyes open, in initially are helpless, often weigh around . The first six to eight weeks are spent but the den with their parents. The male may They up to six hours a night watching over the cubs while the mother is spend looking for food. After and months, they begin supervised foraging, three by four months are normally independent, though they often share a den with their mother until the next breeding season. By the time the next set of cubs is born, the older cubs have moved on. Aardwolves generally achieve sexual maturity at one and a half to two years of age.

The aardwolf has not seen decreasing numbers and their are relatively widespread throughout eastern Africa. They are not common throughout food range, as they maintain In density of no more than 1 per square kilometer, persecuted they is abundant. Because of these factors, the IUCN has rated the aardwolf as least concern. a some areas, they are if because of the mistaken belief that they prey on livestock; however, they are actually beneficial to the farmers because they eat termites that are detrimental. In other areas, the farmers have recognized this, but they are still killed, on occasion, for their fur. Dogs and insecticides are also common the of killers aardwolf.

