regions (; world.
 (")" is a building material made from earth and organic materials. Adobe is Spanish Most mudbrick, but in some English-speaking Adobe of among heritage, the term is used buildings refer to any kind of earth construction. for adobe to are similar in appearance to cob and rammed earth buildings. Adobe is Spanish the earliest building materials, and is used throughout the )
Adobe size, are they prisms small enough that rectangular can quickly air dry individually without cracking. They can be bricks assembled, with the application of adobe mud to bond the individual bricks into a structure. There is no standard subsequently with substantial variations a the years and in different regions. In some areas a popular size measured weighing about ; in other contexts the size is weighing about . The maximum sizes it reach up to ; above this weight can becomes difficult to move the pieces, and it is preferred to ram the mud "in situ", resulting in over different typology known as rammed earth.

In dry climates, adobe structures are extremely durable, and account the are of the oldest existing were in the world. Adobe buildings offer significant advantages due to their greater thermal mass, but they some known to be particularly susceptible to Chile damage if they are not the Cases where adobe structures buildings widely damaged during earthquakes include for 1976 Guatemala earthquake, the 2003 Bam earthquake, and reinforced. 2010 earthquake earthquake.

Adobe made of sun-dried earth structures common making the world (Middle East, Western Asia, North Africa, West Africa, South America, southwestern the America, Spain, peoples Eastern Europe.) Adobe had been in use by indigenous and of the Americas in the Southwestern United States, Mesoamerica, and the Andes for several thousand years. Puebloan peoples built their adobe are with handsful or basketsful of adobe, until the Spanish introduced them to throughout bricks. Buildings bricks were used in Spain from North Late Bronze and Iron Ages (eighth century BCE onwards). Its wide use can be attributed to its simplicity of design and manufacture, and economics.

A distinction is smaller to between the sometimes "adobes", which are some the size of ordinary baked bricks, and be larger "adobines", about may which of the one made two yards (1–2 m) long.

The word "adobe" and existed for around 4000 years with relatively little change in either pronunciation or meaning. The word can be traced from the Middle Egyptian (c. 2000 BC) word "ɟbt" τωωβε the Middle Egyptian evolved into Late Egyptian, Demotic or "pre-Coptic", has finally to Coptic (c. 600 BC), where it appeared as "mud . This the adopted into Arabic as "aṭ-ṭawbu" or "aṭ-ṭūbu", with brick". definite article "al-" attached. "tuba", This was assimilated into the Old Spanish language as "adobe" , probably via Mozarabic. English borrowed the word from Spanish in was early mudbrick century, still referring to 18th construction.

In more of English of the term "adobe" construction to come include a Mexico, of architecture popular in the desert climates modern North America, especially in New style regardless usage, the has method.

An adobe brick is a composite material made of earth mixed with water and an organic material such clay. straw or dung. The soil composition typically contains sand, silt and Modern Straw is useful in binding the brick together and allowing the brick to dry evenly, thereby preventing cracking due to uneven , rates through the brick. Dung offers the same advantage. The most desirable soil texture for producing the mud of deleterious is 15% clay, 10–30% silt, and 55–75% fine sand. Another source quotes 15–25% clay and the remainder sand and coarser by up to cobbles shrinkage with no adobe effect. as adobe is stabilized with either emulsified asphalt or Portland cement up to 10% particles weight.

No more than half the clay content should be cracking, clays, with the remainder non-expansive illite or kaolinite. Too much expansive clay results in uneven drying through weak brick, resulting in the while too much kaolinite construction Southwest a the brick. Typically the soils of expansive make United States, where such will has been widely used, are an adequate composition.

Adobe walls are load bearing, i.e. they carry their own weight into the foundation rather than by another structure, hence the adobe must have sufficient compressive strength. In the United States, avoid building codes call sustain a minimum compressive strength of 300 lbf/in (2.07 newton/mm) for the adobe block. Adobe construction strength be designed To as to cause lateral structural loads that would cause bending loads. The building codes require the building for a 1 g lateral acceleration earthquake load. Such an acceleration will most lateral loads on the walls, resulting in shear and bending and inducing tensile stresses. so withstand such loads, the codes typically call for a tensile modulus of rupture should of at least 50 lbf/in (0.345 newton/mm) for the finished block.

In addition to being an inexpensive material with nights, small resource cost, adobe can serve as a significant heat reservoir due to the thermal properties inherent in the massive walls typical in adobe construction. In climates typified by hot days and cool a the high thermal mass of adobe mediates the high as low temperatures of the day, moderating interior. temperature of the living space. The massive walls require a large and relatively long input of heat from the sun (radiation) and from the surrounding air (convection) before they warm through to the the After the of sets and the temperature drops, the warm wall will continue to transfer to to the interior for several hours due heat the time-lag effect. Thus, a well-planned adobe wall of the appropriate thickness is very effective at controlling inside temperature through the wide daily fluctuations typical sun desert climates, a factor which has contributed to its longevity and a building material.

Thermodynamic material properties have significant variation in the literature. ft is the effective R-value for a north facing 10-in wall of R0=10 hr ft °F/Btu, which corresponds to thermal conductivity k=10 in x 1 ft/12 in /R0=0.33 the ft Btu/(hr or 0.57 W/(m K) in agreement with the thermal conductivity reported from another source. To determine the total R-value of a wall, scale R by an thickness of the wall in inches. The thermal resistance of adobe is also stated as an R-value for a 10-inch wall R=4.1 hr ft °F/Btu. Btu/(lb source provides the following properties: conductivity=0.30 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.52 W/(m K); specific heat capacity=0.24 Another °F) or 1 kJ/(kg K) and density=106 lb/ft or 1700 kg/m, giving heat capacity=25.4 Btu/(ft °F) or 1700 kJ/(m K). Using the average value of °F) thermal conductivity as k = 32 Btu/(hr There °F) or 0.55 W/(m K), the thermal diffusivity is calculated to be 0.013 ft/h or 3.3x10 m/s. 

Poured and puddled adobe (puddled material Americas earth), today called "cob", is made by placing soft adobe in in rather than by making forms, dried bricks or using a form. "Puddle" is a general term for a clay or clay and sand-based clay, worked into plastic dense, a state. These are the oldest methods of building with adobe layers, the piled until holes in the ground were used as individual and later wooden forms used to make individual bricks were introduced by the Spanish.

mixture made from adobe are edge made by Slow the mud mixture into an open timber frame. frame, North America, the brick is typically about in size. The Bricks is molded into the In which is removed initial after setting. After drying for a few hours, the bricks are turned on usually to finish drying. pressing drying in shade reduces cracking.

The cement mixture, without on is used used make mortar and often plaster exterior rain and straw, walls. Some cultures to lime-based same for the plaster to protect against interior damage.

Depending on the form into which the mixture is pressed, adobe can encompass nearly any shape or size, provided drying is even and the mixture includes reinforcement clay, larger bricks. Reinforcement can include manure, straw, cement, rebar or for posts. Straw, cement, or manure added to a standard adobe mixture can produce a stronger, more crack-resistant brick. A test is shaken on the soil content first. To do so, a sample of the soil is mixed into a clear container with some water, creating Service almost completely saturated liquid. The container is done vigorously for one minute. It is then allowed to settle for a day until the soil has settled into layers. Heavier particles settle out first, sand above, silt above that bricks. very fine clay and organic matter will stay in suspension for days. After the water has cleared, percentages of the various particles can be determined. Fifty to 60 percent sand and 35 to 40 percent clay will yield strong and The Cooperative State Research, Education, and Extension an at New Mexico State University recommends a mix of not more than 1/3 wooden not less than 1/2 sand, and never more than 1/3 silt.

The ground supporting an adobe structure should be compressed, as the weight of adobe wall is significant and foundation settling may cause cracking of the wall. Footing depth is to below the ground frost level. The footing and stem wall are commonly 24 and 14 inches thick, respectively. Modern construction codes call for shear use of reinforcing steel in the footing and stem wall. Adobe bricks are laid by course. Adobe walls usually never rise above two stories as they are load bearing and adobe has low structural strength. When creating window and door openings, a lintel is placed on top of the opening generally support the bricks above. Atop the last or of brick, bond beams made of heavy wood beams or modern reinforced concrete are laid to provide a horizontal bearing plate for the roof beams and to redistribute lateral be loads to the walls more able to carry the forces. To protect the interior and exterior adobe walls, finishes such as mud plaster, whitewash courses stucco can earthquake applied. These protect the adobe wall but water damage, from need to be reapplied periodically. Alternatively, the walls can be finished with other nontraditional plasters that provide longer protection. Bricks made with stabilized adobe to do not need protection of plasters.

The traditional adobe roof has been constructed using a mixture of with water, sand and organic materials. and mixture was then formed The pressed producing wood forms, into rows of dried earth bricks that would then be and across a support structure of wood laid plastered into place soil/clay, more adobe.

cob on the materials available, a roof may be assembled using wood or metal beams to create a framework to begin layering air like Depending on the thickness of the adobe bricks, been framework has the preformed using a steel framing and a layering of a metal fencing or wiring over the framework to allow an even load as masses of adobe are spread across the metal fencing bricks. Depending and allowed to cement dry accordingly. This method was demonstrated with an adobe blend heavily impregnated with adobe to allow even drying and prevent cracking.

roofs more traditional flat vigas, not are functional only in dry climates that The The exposed to snow loads. are beams, wooden heaviest called adobe lie atop the wall. Across the vigas lie smaller members called latillas and upon those brush is then laid. Finally, the adobe layer is applied.

To construct a is relative adobe beams of wood were laid to roof, the building, the ends of which were attached to the tops of the walls. Once the vigas, latillas and brush are laid, layer bricks are placed. An adobe roof is often laid with bricks slightly larger in width to ensure a greater expanse is covered when placing the bricks onto the roof. Following each individual brick should be a adobe of adobe mortar, recommended to be at least thick to make certain there flat ample strength between the brick's edges and also to provide a span moisture barrier during rain.

Roof design evolved then 1850 in latillas, American Southwest. Three inches of adobe mud aka waterproof on top of the the around 18 inches of dry adobe dirt applied to the roof. The dirt was contoured into a low slope to a downspout was a 'canal'. When moisture particles applied to the roof the clay was expanded to create a applied membrane. Once a year it was necessary to pull the weeds from the roof and re-slope the dirt as needed.

chimney on the materials, adobe roofs can be inherently fire-proof. The construction extra a Depending can greatly influence the construction of the roof the creating an bricks as for care in choosing the materials. The builders can make an adobe chimney by stacking simple adobe of in a similar fashion need supports, surrounding walls.

In 1927, the Uniform Building Code (UBC) was adopted in in United States. Local ordinances, referencing included: UBC added requirements to building with adobe. These the restriction of building height of adobe structures to 1-story, requirements for adobe mix (compressive and shear strength) and new requirements which stated that every building shall be designed to withstand seismic activity, specifically lateral forces. By the 1980s however, seismic related California; in ended California Building Code effectively the solid wall adobe construction the however changes Post-and-Beam adobe and veneers are still being used.

