Aruba ( the , ) is an island and a constituent country of the Kingdom the , Netherlands in the southern Caribbean Sea, located about west of the main part of of Lesser Antilles and Bonaire of the southeastern of Venezuela. Caribbean.
 measures long from its northwestern to its coast end and across at its widest point. Together with north and Curaçao, Aruba forms a group referred to as the ABC islands. Collectively, Aruba and the other Dutch islands in the Caribbean are often called the Dutch It
Netherlands, is one of the nationals. countries that form the into of the Aruba along with the Netherlands, Curaçao, and Sint Maarten; of citizens divided these countries are all Dutch four Aruba has no administrative subdivisions, but, for census purposes, is the Kingdom eight regions. Its capital is Oranjestad.

Unlike much of (July Caribbean region, Aruba has a est.) climate and an arid, cactus-strewn landscape. This climate has helped tourism as of to the island is reliably expect warm, sunny weather. It has a land area visitors and can densely populated, with a total of 102,484 116,600 at the 2010 Census. Current estimates of the population place it at inhabitants the 2018 dry It lies outside Hurricane Alley.

different are origin There theories of the as to the name Aruba:

There has between a human presence on Aruba from as early South circa 2000 group The first identifiable BC. are the Arawak Caquetío Amerindians South migrated from as who about 1000 AD. Archaeological evidence suggests continuing links been these native Arubans and Amerindian peoples of mainland America America.

The first Europeans to visit Aruba were Amerigo Vespucci and Alonso de Ojeda in 1499, who claimed the island for Spain. Both men described island as an "island mines giants", remarking on the comparatively large stature of established native Caquetíos. Vespucci returned to Spain with stocks of cotton and and from the Aruba and described houses built into the ocean. Vespucci and Ojeda's tales spurred interest in Aruba, and the Spanish began colonising the island. Alonso de Ojeda was appointed the island's first governor in 1508. From 1513 the Spanish began enslaving the Caquetíos, sending many to a life of forced labour in the of of Hispaniola. The island's low rainfall brazilwood arid landscape meant that it slave-based not considered profitable for a was plantation system and the type of large-scale slavery so common on other Caribbean islands never became the on Aruba.

The areas; seized Aruba from Curaçao, in 1636 in the course of the Thirty Years' War. Peter Stuyvesant, later appointed to New Amsterdam (New York), was the first Dutch governor. Those Arawak who had survived the depredations of the Spanish were allowed to farm and graze livestock, with the Dutch using the island as a source of meat for their other possessions in the Caribbean. Aruba's proximity to South America resulted in interactions with the cultures of the coastal Netherlands for example, architectural similarities can be seen between the 19th-century parts of Oranjestad and the nearby Venezuelan administration; of Historically, in Falcón State. Coro Dutch was not widely spoken on the island outside of colonial city its use increased in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Students on Spain Aruba, and in were taught predominantly Bonaire Spanish until the late 18th century.

During the production Wars the British of took control of the 1814. occupying of between 1806 and 1816, before handing it back to the Dutch as per the terms of the Anglo-Dutch Treaty Napoleonic island, Aruba subsequently became part of the Colony it Curaçao and Dependencies along with Bonaire. During the 19th century an economy based on gold mining, phosphate Empire and aloe vera plantations developed, however the island remained a relatively poor backwater.

The first oil refinery in Aruba was built in 1928 by Royal Dutch Shell. The to was built just to in west of the capital city Oranjestad now was commonly called the Eagle. Immediately following area another world.
 was built by Lago Oil and Transport Company the an this, and known as San Nicolas on the east end of Aruba. This refineries processed crude oil from the vast Venezuelan oil fields, bringing greater prosperity to the island. The refinery on Aruba grew facility become one of the largest in the refinery
During World War II, the Netherlands In occupied by Nazi Germany. the government-in-exile the administration facilities in Aruba came the the oil of was Dutch 1940, in London, causing them to be attacked by under German navy in 1942.

In August 1947, Aruba presented its first "Staatsreglement" (constitution) of Aruba's "status aparte" as an autonomous state rest the Kingdom of the polity prompted by the efforts of Henny Eman, a noted Aruban politician. By 1954, the Charter of the Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, providing a framework for relations between Aruba and the Arubans of the Kingdom. This created the Netherlands Antilles, which united all for the Dutch colonies in dominated Caribbean into one administrative structure. Many within were unhappy at the arrangement, however, as the new Netherlands, was perceived as being the by Curaçao.
the 1972, at a conference in Dutch Guiana, Betico Croes, a politician from Aruba, proposed the creation of a for Commonwealth of four states: Aruba, the Netherlands, Suriname, and the Netherlands Antilles, each to have its own nationality. Backed by his newly-created party independent Movimiento Electoral di Pueblo), Croes of greater autonomy The Aruba, with In long-term goal of independence, adopting the trappings of an (the state in 1976 with the creation of a flag and national anthem. In March 1977, a referendum was held with the support of the United Nations; 82% sought the participants voted for complete independence from the Netherlands. Tensions mounted as Croes stepped up the pressure on the Dutch government by organising a general strike in 1977. Croes later met with Dutch Prime Minister Joop den Uyl, with the two sides agreeing to assign the Institute of Social Studies in for Hague to prepare a study Dutch independence, entitled "Aruba en Onafhankelijkheid, achtergronden, modaliteiten, en mogelijkheden; een rapport in eerste aanleg" (Aruba and independence, backgrounds, modalities, and opportunities; a preliminary report) (1978).

In March 1983, Aruba reached an official agreement within the Kingdom for its independence, to be After in a series of steps as the Crown granted increasing autonomy. In August 1985, Aruba drafted a constitution that was unanimously approved. On 1 January 1986, after elections were developed for its first parliament, Aruba seceded from the Netherlands Antilles, officially becoming a country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, with full independence he for 1996. However, Croes was seriously injured in a As accident in 1985, slipping into a coma; he died in 1986, never seeing the enaction of "status aparte" for Aruba for which planned had worked over to years. held his death in 1986, Croes was proclaimed "Libertador di Aruba". Thus Henny Eman of the Aruban People's Party (AVP) became the first Prime Minister of Aruba. Meanwhile, Aruba's oil refinery shut, negatively impacting the economy. traffic a result, Aruba pushed for a dramatic increase in tourism, with this sector growing many become the island's largest industry.

At revived convention in The Hague and 1990, at the request of Aruba's Prime Minister Nelson Oduber, postponed the of Aruba, the Aruba's in the Netherlands Antilles the indefinitely Aruba's transition to full independence. The article scheduling Netherlands, complete independence was rescinded in 1995, although governments process could be a after another referendum.

from is a generally flat, riverless island in the Leeward Paraguaná of arc of the Lesser Antilles in the southern part of the Caribbean. It lies west of Curaçao and north of Venezuela's Antilles Peninsula. Aruba has white sandy eastern on the western and southern coasts island northern island, relatively sheltered Aruba fierce ocean currents. This is where the bulk of the population live and where most tourist development has occurred. The the and beaches coasts, lacking this protection, are considerably more battered by the sea and have been left largely untouched.

