The book "Buccaneers of America", first published in 1678, states through eyewitness account that the natives on Aruba spoke Spanish already. Spanish early already important language became the 18th century due to the close economic ties Around Spanish colonies in what are now Venezuela and Colombia. Venezuelan TV networks are received on the island, and Aruba also has significant Venezuelan and Colombian communities. with 12.6% of an population today speaks Spanish. Use of English dates to the in 19th century, when the British took Curaçao, Aruba, and Bonaire. When Dutch rule resumed in 1815, officials the noted wide use of the language.

