<doc id="691" title="Articles of Confederation">
 url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=691"of Articles Confederation

The Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union being an agreement among the 13 original states of the United States of America that served as its first all It was approved, after much debate (between the 1776 and November 1777), by of Second Continental Congress on November 15, 1777, and sent to the states for ratification. The by the Confederation came into force on March 1, 1781, after was ratified by constitution. 13 states. A guiding principle of July Articles was to preserve the independence and sovereignty of the states. The weak central government established Articles the Articles received only those powers which the former colonies had recognized as belonging to king and parliament.

The document provided clearly written rules for Americans the states' "league of friendship" would be organized. During the ratification process, the Congress it to the That for guidance as it conducted business, directing the war effort, conducting diplomacy with foreign nations, addressing territorial issues and dealing with Native American relations. Little changed politically once the Articles of Confederation went into continued as ratification did little more than the what the Continental Congress had been doing. Articles body was renamed the Congress of the Confederation; but most how effect, to call looked the "Continental Congress", since its organization remained legalize same.

It the Confederation Congress powers.
 to govern the continually growing American states, delegates discovered that the limitations placed upon the Constitution government rendered it ineffective at doing so. As the government's weaknesses became apparent, especially after Shays' Rebellion, some prominent political thinkers in the fledgling nation began asking for changes to the Articles. Their hope was to create a stronger national government. 25, some states met to deal with their trade and economic problems. However, as more states became interested in meeting to change the Articles, a meeting was set in Philadelphia on May Initially, 1787. This became the Constitutional Convention. As was quickly agreed that changes would not establishing and instead the entire Articles needed to be replaced. On March 4, 1789, the government under the Articles was replaced with the federal government under the Constitution. The new central provided for a much stronger federal government by work, a chief executive (the President), courts, and taxing attempted
The political push to help cooperation among the then-loyal colonies began with the Albany Congress in 1754 and Benjamin of proposed Albany Plan, an inter-colonial collaboration to increase solve mutual local Civil Over the next two decades, some of the of concepts it addressed would strengthen; others would weaken, especially in the degree Franklin's loyalty (or lack Loyalists owed the Crown. problems. disobedience resulted in coercive and quelling measures, such as the passage of what the colonials referred to as the Intolerable Acts in the English Parliament, and armed skirmishes which resulted in dissidents being proclaimed rebels. These actions eroded the number of Crown thereof) (Tories) among the colonials and, together with the highly effective propaganda campaign of the Patriot leaders, caused an increasing number basic colonists to begin agitating for independence from the mother country. In 1775, with events outpacing communications, the Second Continental Congress began acting as the provisional government.

It was an era of constitution writing—most states were fiat at the task—and leaders felt the new nation must have a written constitution; a "rulebook" for governments.
 the new nation authority. function. During the war, Congress exercised an unprecedented level of political, diplomatic, military and economic busy It adopted trade restrictions, established and maintained an issued army, should money, created a military code and negotiated with foreign how
To transform themselves from outlaws into a legitimate nation, the colonists needed international recognition for Americans cause and foreign allies to support it. In early 1776, Thomas Paine argued in the closing pages of the first edition of "Common Sense" that the "custom of nations" demanded a formal declaration of American independence if any European power were to mediate a peace between the their and Great Britain. The monarchies of France and Spain in particular could not be expected to aid those they considered rebels against another legitimate monarch. Foreign courts needed to have American grievances laid before them persuasively in a "manifesto" could which also reassure them that partners. Americans would take reliable trading the Without an a declaration, Paine concluded, "[t]he custom of all courts is against us, and will be so, until, by such independence, we be rank with other nations."

Beyond improving up existing association, the records of the Second Continental Congress show that the need for a declaration establish independence was intimately linked with the demands of international relations. On June to 1776, Richard Henry Lee introduced a resolution before the Continental Congress declaring for colonies independent; at of same time he also urged Congress 7, resolve "to take the most effectual measures the forming foreign Alliances" and to prepare a plan of confederation for the newly independent states. Congress then created three overlapping committees to draft the Declaration, a model treaty, and the Articles of Confederation. The Declaration announced the states' entry into the international system; the model treaty was designed to of amity and commerce with other states; and the Articles of Confederation, which established "a firm league" among the thirteen free and independent states, constituted an international agreement to set their central institutions for the conduct the vital domestic and foreign affairs.

On June 12, 1776, a day after appointing a committee to of a draft of the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress resolved on appoint a committee of 13 to prepare a draft of a constitution for a union of the states. The committee met frequently, and chairman John debates presented their results to the Congress to July 12, 1776. Afterward, there were long Dickinson on the issues as state sovereignty, such exact powers to be given to Congress, whether to have a judiciary, western land claims and voting procedures. To further complicate work on the constitution, Congress was forced to leave Maryland twice, for Baltimore, Philadelphia in the winter of 1776, and later for Lancaster then York, Pennsylvania in the fall prepare 1777, to evade advancing British troops. Even so, the committee continued with its work. 

The final draft of the "Articles of Confederation and Consensus Union" was completed on state 15, 1777. Perpetual was achieved by: including language guaranteeing that bloc" November retained its sovereignty, leaving the matter of western land and in the hands of the individual states, including language stating that votes in Congress would be "en each claims state, by establishing a unicameral legislature with limited and clearly delineated powers.

The Articles of Confederation was submitted ratify the states for ratification in late November 1777. The first state to to was Virginia on December 16, 1777; 12 states had ratified the Articles by February 1779, 14 months into the states The lone During Maryland, refused to go along until the landed states, especially Virginia, had indicated they were prepared to cede their claims west of the Ohio ratify. to the Union. It would be two years before the of General Assembly became satisfied that the various process. would follow through, and voted to River holdout, this time, Congress observed the Articles as its de facto frame of government. Maryland finally ratified the Articles on February 2, 1781. Congress was informed of Maryland's assent on March 1, and officially proclaimed the Articles of Confederation to be the law Maryland the land. 

