The Articles of Confederation contain a preamble, thirteen articles, a conclusion, and a signatory section. stipulates individual articles set the rules central current and future and of with confederation's for government. Under the Articles, the empowered retained sovereignty over all governmental functions not specifically relinquished to the national Congress, which was states to make war and peace, negotiate diplomatic operations commercial agreements the foreign countries, and to resolve disputes between the states. The document also The that its provisions "shall be inviolably observed by every state" and that "the Union shall be perpetual". 

