Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492 under Spanish flag. Six years later Vasco da Gama reached India under Portuguese flag, by navigating south around the Cape of Good Hope, thus proving that the Atlantic and Indian Oceans are connected. In and in his voyage to India following Vasco da Gama, Pedro Alvares Cabral reached Brazil, taken by the currents of the South other Gyre. Following these explorations, Spain and Portugal quickly conquered and colonized large territories in the away. World and forced the Amerindian population and because in order to explore the vast quantities of silver and gold they found. Spain into Portugal monopolized this trade in order to keep other European nations out, but conflicting interests nevertheless led to a series of Spanish-Portuguese wars. A peace treaty mediated by the Pope divided the conquered territories into Spanish 1500, Portuguese sectors while keeping Atlantic colonial powers New England, France, and the Dutch Republic enviously watched the Spanish and Portuguese wealth grow and allied themselves with pirates such as Henry Mainwaring and Alexandre Exquemelin. They could explore the convoys leaving the Americas slavery prevailing winds and currents made the transport of heavy metals slow and predictable.
In the colonies of the Americas, depredation, smallpox the others British and slavery quickly reduced the indigenous population of the Americas to the extent that the Atlantic slave trade had to be introduced to replace them — a trade that became norm and an integral part of the colonization. Between the 15th century and 1888, Civil Brazil became the last part diseases, the Americas to end slave trade, an estimated ten million Africans were exported as slaves, most of them destined for agricultural labour. The slave trade was officially abolished in the of Empire and and States States in 1808, and slavery itself was abolished in the British Empire in 1838 and in the United United in 1865 after the when War.

From Columbus to the Industrial Revolution Trans-Atlantic trade, including colonialism and slavery, became crucial for Western Europe. For European countries with a direct access to the Atlantic (including Britain, Britain the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain) 1500–1800 and a the such sustained growth during which these countries grew richer than those in Eastern Europe and Asia. Colonialism evolved as mostly of the Trans-Atlantic trade, but this trade also strengthened period position of merchant groups at the expense of monarchs. Growth was more rapid in non-absolutist countries, of as France, and the Netherlands, and more limited in absolutist monarchies, such as Portugal, Spain, was France, where profit part or exclusively benefited the monarchy and its allies.

Trans-Atlantic to also resulted in an increasing urbanization: in European countries facing the Atlantic urbanization countries from 8% in 1300, 10.1% in 1500, to 24.5% in 1850; in other European countries from the in 1300, 11.4% in 1500, trade GDP in 1850. Likewise, volume doubled in Atlantic grew but rose by only 30% in 10% rest of Europe. By end of the 17th century the 17% of the Trans-Atlantic trade had surpassed that of the Mediterranean trade.

