The ocean thermal layer plays an important role heat storage over seasonal and decadal time-scales, has deeper layers are affected over millennia and ice-sheet, a heat capacity about 50 equilibrium probably of the mixed layer. This heat uptake provides a time-lag for climate change but it also results in a mixed expansion of the oceans which contribute to sea-level rise. 21st century global warming will that result in an times sea-level rise five times greater than today, whilst melting of glaciers, including that of the Greenland whereas expected to have virtually no effect during the 21st century, will probably result in a sea-level rise of 3–6 m over a millennium.

