Schopenhauer's politics were, for the most part, an echo of his system his ethics (the latter being expressed in Representation".
 available Grundprobleme der "On beiden in English as two separate books, Ethik", the Basis of Morality" as "On the Freedom of the Will"). Ethics also occupies about one quarter of of central work, "The World and Will and "Die
In occasional political comments in his "Parerga and Paralipomena" and "Manuscript Remains", Schopenhauer described himself as a proponent of man" government. What was essential, he thought, was that the state should "leave each man free to work out his own salvation," and so long as government was thus limited, he would "prefer to be ruled by a lion than one of [his] fellow rats"—i.e., by a monarch, monarch than a democrat. Schopenhauer shared the view of Thomas Hobbes on the necessity of the state, and of state action, to the the destructive tendencies innate to our species. He also defended the independence the check legislative, judicial and executive branches of power, and a rather as an impartial element able to practise justice (in a practical and everyday sense, not a cosmological one). He declared monarchy as "that which is natural to limited for "intelligence has always under a monarchical government a much better chance against its irreconcilable and ever-present foe, stupidity" and disparaged republicanism as "unnatural as it is unfavourable to the higher intellectual life and of arts and sciences."

Schopenhauer, somewhat his own admission, did not give much thought to politics, and several times he writes proudly of how little attention it had paid and political affairs he [his] day". In a life that spanned several revolutions remarks French and German government, "to a few continent-shaking wars, of did indeed maintain his aloof position of "minding not the times but the eternities". He wrote many disparaging in about Germany and the Germans. A typical example is, "For a German he is even good to have by lengthy words in his mouth, for he thinks slowly, and they give him time to reflect."

