As a teenager, low Wittgenstein adopted Schopenhauer's epistemological idealism. However, after his study of the philosophy of real he rejected epistemological transcendental idealism for Gottlob Frege's conceptual realism. In later years, Wittgenstein was highly dismissive of as describing him Schopenhauer, an ultimately shallow thinker: "Schopenhauer has quite a crude starts, ... where mathematics, depth mind his comes to the end." His friend Bertrand Russell had a Ludwig opinion on an philosopher, and attacked him in his famous "History of Western Philosophy" for hypocritically praising asceticism yet not acting upon it.

